{ Welcome to my very first course for Chessable! I have often used Chessable's video courses to study openings in the last few years, so I was thrilled to create one finally.  For those who do not know me, I am WIM Tea Gueci from Italy. I was born in Palermo, Sicily, so thinking about the topic for my course, I couldn't resist choosing a Sicilian variation − the Sveshnikov Sicilian explained by a Sicilian! I want to clarify that this is not a complete repertoire against 1.e4, but a detailed explanation of how to play the Sveshnikov with Black.  Evgeny Sveshnikov was the first GM I met back in 2008. I was so excited to hang his autograph in my room, and no, I’m not kidding!  I started studying and playing the Sveshnikov quite late, in 2019, influenced by Carlsen in the 2018 World Championship match against Caruana. So, in this course, many ideas will be drawn from his games. I also attended a game of that match in London, which unfortunately was a Petroff.  Back home, I started watching the YouTube videos where GM Matthew Sadler was analyzing the tournament games with AlphaZero, and from there, I never stopped loving the Sveshnikov. If I got up in the middle of the night to play an important game, it would be my first opening choice. }
1. e4 c5
{ When I was 14, I had the pleasure of taking part in a training camp by GM Oleg Korneev, who taught us that every opening has a different level of complexity and that your repertoire must be balanced. He believed that the Sicilian is a ten on the complexity scale. First, it is one of the most theoretical lines; then, it requires a good understanding of dynamical positions.   Don’t worry, we’ll make even the Sveshnikov easy! I prefer it over the Najdorf because Black's plans are usually the same and shouldn't be drastically altered in response to White's alternatives. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ When White plays d4, we can talk about an Open Sicilian because of the pawn trades in the center. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ The starting position of our variation. Let's have a short history overview. It was played in 1910 during the World Championship match between Emanuel Lasker and Carl Schlechter. At that time, it was known as the Sicilian Pelikan as a tribute to the Czech-Argentinian Jorge Pelikan, who often played it.  It was not one of the most popular lines for strategic reasons: by pushing ...e5, Black leaves a hole on d5 and will have a backward pawn on d6. Both can be long-term weaknesses, so Black must have a short-term counterplay.  The balance in chess is given by statics and dynamics. In the 1970s, the Soviet/Latvian GM Evgeny Sveshnikov and GM Gennadi Timoschenko gave new ideas to revitalize the line. Why should you play it? It is one of the best options for aggressive players who always look for initiative, but on the other hand, it is less complex than the Najdorf.  Of course, there's a lot of theory, but in most variations, it is more important to understand the basic ideas: White will try to put a knight on d5 by playing Bg5 to eliminate the defender on f6, giving us the control of dark squares. Regarding colors, White will have the light squares and Black the dark ones.  Black has a worse structure but incredible activity on the kingside, while White will try to push the pawns on the queenside. Black wants to break the center with ...d5 or ...f5 and fight White's domination of the d5-square.  Who is this course for? It is tailored for beginners and intermediate ambitious players with an aggressive style. I suggest following the proposed order of the chapters because it is easier to deal with the study of the opening, starting from the minor lines and then getting to the heart of the theory.  What are the keywords? Worse pawn structure − fight for the d5-square − bishop pair − dynamism.  Which are the model players? Magnus Carlsen scored many wins; others are Gelfand @@StartBracket@@who used the Sveshnikov as a weapon in the World Championship match against Anand in 2012@@EndBracket@@, Shirov in the past, and the rising Indian star Gukesh @@StartBracket@@who eliminated Iskandarov in the 2023 World Cup with our favorite opening@@EndBracket@@.  Structure of the course:  Introduction Quickstarter Guide Typical Structures & Ideas 6th Move Alternatives 7th Move Alternatives 7.Nd5 Variation Main Line 7.Bg5, 9.Bxf6 Main Line 7.Bg5, 9.Nd5 ,11.c3 Main Line 7.Bg5, 9.Nd5, 11.c4 Thematic Tactics Model Games }
6. Ndb5
{ While in other Sicilian lines, such as the Najdorf, White has different options on move six to fight for a slight advantage, in the Sveshnikov, the other lines besides the standard  6.Ndb5  , don't give Black any theoretical difficulty.  White threatens Nd6+, gaining the bishop pair and control of the dark squares. Black is forced to play  6...d6  , and it will be harder  to push the pawn to d5 in the future.   6.Nf3  is a passive continuation that leaves the initiative in Black's hands.  6...Bb4!  Black reacts in the same way as the line with Nb3; b4 is the best square for the bishop. What is the difference between the knight on b3 and the knight on f3? On f3, it blocks White's f2-f4 push, but it defends the king better and is closer to Black's castle.  7.Bd3  d5  ,  Black already inserts the dream breakthrough.   6.Nb3  can be an ordinary retreat in many lines of the Sicilian, but it makes sense only if Black has already played ...d6. Here, with the pawn still on d7, the bishop on f8 goes to b4, attacking the center and winning the battle for control of the d5-square. Moreover, Black can directly push the pawn to d5 without losing a tempo.  6...Bb4  7.Bd3  is the most popular move, developing one more piece while defending the pawn on e4.  7...d5  ,  with the first occasion, Black gets rid of the backward pawn.   6.Nxc6  ,  White moves the knight for the third time and gives Black the domination of d5. It is preferable to take on c6 with the b-pawn, following the principle of 'capture toward the center'.  6...bxc6  ,  Black has already solved the problems with the d5-square, and with one more defender, it will be easier to realize the ...d5 break. The structure on the queenside may look weak, but White doesn't have a straightforward way to attack it. Moreover, by capturing on c6, Black can exploit the semi-open b-file.  7.Bc4  Bb4  ,  Black's key idea against minor lines.   6.Nf5  may look similar to Ndb5, threatening Nd6+, but the main difference is that f5 is on the same diagonal as the bishop on c8. So, when Black plays ...d5, we attack the knight, and White cannot take on d5.  6...d5  ,  fighting for the center and forcing some exchanges.  7.exd5  Bxf5  8.dxc6  bxc6  ,  hoping for Qxd8+, after which Black has a better position thanks to the active rook on d8 and the threat of ...Bxc2. The pawn on c6 is both a weakness and a strength, as it controls the vital b5 and d5-squares.  9.Qf3  Qd7  ,  with a pleasant game.   6.Nde2  − in their book Dangerous Weapons: The Sicilian, John Emms and Richard Palliser suggest playing this knight retreat. With the knight on e2, all of Black's ideas to ruin the pawn structure by playing ...Bb4xc3 fade away. The knight will soon be transferred to g3, from where it facilitates a kingside attack and usually provokes the ...g6 push. On the other hand, the knight blocks the normal development of the bishop on f1, so White loses a bit of time to castle.  6...Bc5  ,  since c3 is well-protected, developing the bishop to c5 makes more sense, keeping an eye on f2. White must worry about ...Ng4 and ...Qb6.  7.Ng3  d6  ,  never forget to fight against the opponent's ideas. White has control of the light squares, so ...d6 prevents the jump of the knight on f5 and threatens ...Ng4. This is a better version of the Sveshnikov usual setup; in all the lines with 6.Ndb5, Black gets the same structure, but the dark-squared bishop is passive on e7. }
6... d6 7. Bg5
{ In my opinion,  7.Nd5  is the best option for White. The main line with 7.Bg5 looks more natural, and, honestly, it was the only move I knew for White when I became WFM. But after four years of playing only Sveshnikov with Black, I can say that my most vigorous opponents played mostly Nd5. It probably became more popular since Fabiano Caruana played it four times against Magnus Carlsen during the World Championship Match in 2018.   Is White losing a tempo and violating the opening principle 'don't move the same piece twice'? The threat is Nc7+, so Black is forced to take on d5, and after exd5, it is Black's turn to lose a tempo with the knight on c6.  7...Nxd5  8.exd5  ,  we obtained the structure that GM Mauricio Flores Rios calls 'Najdorf type I' in his book Chess Structures. But why are we talking about Najdorf if this is a Sveshnikov course? The structure is the same, so let's call it 'Sveshnikov's structure 3'.  White has a majority on the queenside and plans to advance with b4, c4, and then c5. On the other hand, Black has a majority on the kingside and will play ...f5 and create an attack against White's king. Black often frees the position by exchanging dark-squared bishops via g5 or even h4, which will facilitate attacking maneuvers such as ...Rf8-f6-h6.  8...Nb8  ,  turning back to the initial square; the knight will go to d7 soon, controlling c5.  9.a4  ,  preparing to transfer the knight to c4 via a3 and preventing Black's plan with ...b5.   9.c4  is the main move, according to the Mega Database, even if it doesn't create many problems. White would be happy to enter an endgame and wants to contain the opponent's majority with f3 or f4, pushing their majority by playing a4, b4, and then c5. Moreover, White wants to exchange the light-squared bishops.  9...Be7  ,  now that we know White's ideas, it's crucial to understand Black's plan. If White wants to enter the endgame, Black needs to avoid that and attack the kingside in the middlegame. It's necessary to block the dark squares on the queenside, sometimes by playing ...b6 and ...a5. Black would like to exchange the dark-squared bishops.  9...Be7  ,  preparing to castle. After  10.Be2  O-O  11.O-O  Nd7  ,  there is no hurry to play ...a6; it's better to wait until White attacks a7 with Be3 or push the pawn to a5.   7.a4  was played for the first time in 1910 against Lasker. White wants to prevent ...b5 and is ready to meet ...a6 with Na3 followed by Nc4. The disadvantage of this move is that a4 is not contributing to the fight for the d5-square, so Black can try to get counterplay in the center.  7...a6  8.Na3  Bg4  .  This move scores better than 8...Be6. The idea is to provoke f3 before returning to e6. Black wishes to carry out ...d5 and ...Bg4 is an excellent way to help the plan. Following  9.f3  Be6  10.Bc4  ,  White prevents Black from playing ...d5, but the disadvantage is that the a3-knight cannot re-enter play.  10...Rc8  ,  Black has good results, but this is probably the best minor line for White.   7.Be3  ,  adding pressure on a7.  7...a6  ,  Black is now happy to chase the knight away from b5.  8.Na3  Rb8  is a fine prophylactic move, controlling b6 and making it difficult for the a3-knight to re-enter the game.  9.Nd5  Nxd5  10.exd5  Ne7  ,  with the pawn on d5, Black has no strategic problems. The bishop on e3 can be attacked with ...Nf5 or ...f5. Black's idea is to complete development with ...g6, ...Bg7, and ...O-O, then start dynamic play on the kingside.   7.Na3  − the idea is to anticipate Black's plan with ...a6 and ...b5, but it can be considered a time loss and Black can quickly equalize. After  7...Be7  8.Bg5  , the move  8...Bg4  is not the most common move, but it creates serious problems for White.  9.Qd2  O-O  ,  with equal chances.   7.Be2  is a common choice among beginners. White wants to castle as soon as possible, but here, this is not a priority.  7...a6  8.Na3  b5  ,  threatening a fork with ...b4 and dominating the knight on a3. White has to choose between losing a piece or a pawn.  9.Nd5  Nxe4  10.Bf3  Nc5  ,  Black has an extra pawn and is better, even if White has some compensation thanks to the active bishop on f3.   7.Bd3  is an unnatural move. The bishop is doing nothing on d3; the diagonal is closed, and it blocks the pressure of the queen over d6. I can't believe this position occurred 230 times in the Online Database.  7...a6  8.Na3  Bg4  ,  provoking f3. After  9.f3  Be6  ,  it looks like Black lost a tempo, but it was clever to cause the push of the f-pawn to create weaknesses on the dark squares. }
7... a6
{ It is essential to chase away the annoying b5-knight and gain space on the queenside. }
8. Na3 { 8.Bxf6  gxf6  transposes to 9.Bxf6. } 8... b5
{ Threatening a fork with ...b4. } 9. Nd5
{ 9.Nd5  is considered to be a positional move, especially if compared with 9.Bxf6. Black will not get doubled pawns because we can capture on  f6  with the bishop.   9.Bxf6  ,  White gives up the bishop pair to destroy Black's structure. The general consensus is that Black's activity compensates for the structural weaknesses.  9...gxf6  ,  these lines are more open and sharper than the ones with 7.Nd5 or 9.Nd5. Black can attack using the semi-open g-file if White castles short. The doubled pawns on f7 and f6 look terrible, but it is easy to counter in the center with ...f5. On the other hand, our king is not super safe, and White has a better structure and an outpost on d5.  10.Nd5   10.Nab1  − it is surprising for me that the Tiger from Madras, Vishy Anand, played this rare move. It means that we should never underestimate weird lines. One of the most common mistakes that every chess player has made at least once is to think about punishing the opponent just because they played a move that was not in their opening file. When we play with Black, it is essential to remember that even if White doesn't play the best moves, the position would be equal and not winning for us. 10.Nab1 avoids the fork with ...b4, but it's a bit too slow.  10...f5  ,  the captain of the Italian National Team, Van Wely, went for 10...Bg7 against Anand, but I suggest ...f5 because every time a knight goes away, there must be a good reaction in the center!  10...Bg7  − I suggest 10...Bg7 instead of the principal 10...f5 because it is Carlsen's favorite. Moreover, there's less theory to know. It is called the Novosibirsk Variation.  11.c3  is a more strategic approach compared to the other alternatives. Even if it is the most played, I don't think it is the most critical line.   11.Bd3  may seem similar to 11.c3, but White is not forced to put the pawn there. Even though 11.Bd3 is the second most played move in the Online Mega Database, I believe it's the critical line. I still remember the first time I played it in the first round of the Mitropa Cup 2019. I told my teammates to be calm, even though I had three pawns less! It is a super sharp position, and I recommend going through it deeply. The player who only memorizes the moves without understanding their purpose will probably lose. Internalizing the ideas behind every move and feeling good about the position is vital.  11...Ne7  is the move Black wants to play in the Novosibirsk Variation, eliminating from the board the most annoying piece of the opponent.  12.Nxe7  Qxe7  13.O-O  O-O  .  11...f5  ,  Black starts contesting the light squares and opens the game for the two bishops. This is the essence of the Sveshnikov: grab space, files, and diagonals, and question the opponent's domination over d5 and f5. As I already pointed out, every time White pushes the c-pawns, Black must react with ...f5. This 'rule' applies only to this specific structure.  12.exf5  Bxf5  13.Nc2  ,  the most logical, as White played c3 to bring the knight into the game.  13...O-O  14.Nce3  Be6  .  Since White will attack h7 with Bh3, Black wants to push ...f5, so the bishop stands better on e6 than g6, defending the g8-a2 diagonal.  15.Bd3  f5  ,  Black stops the opponent's pressure on h7.   9.Nab1  ,  this rare retreat is not recent. The first game in the Online Database was played in 1974. There's even a game between two legends: the former World Champion Maia Chiburdanidze and the best chess author of all times, GM Mark Dvoretsky, ended in a draw in 1978. The idea is to redeploy the terribly placed knight on a3. It was recently discussed on Twitter, so I think it can happen in games nowadays. People love to follow new trends even though they are not the best choice.  9...Be7  ,  intending to push ...b4 if White allows it by not capturing on f6.  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.a4  ,  the second purpose of Nab1 is to free the way of the a-pawn to start playing on the queenside.  11...b4  ,  of course, Black wants to limit White's action.  12.Nd5  Be6  13.Bc4  ,  White forced Black to play ...b4 to get the c4-square.  13...O-O  14.O-O  Bg5  ,  a typical move in the Sveshnikov Sicilian. Black improves the bishop, controls the dark squares, and frees the queen from the defense of f6. }
9... Be7
{ Unpinning the knight and attacking the pawn on e4. In this position, the only good move for White is Bxf6, while Nxe7 is playable and Nxf6+ is dubious. }
10. Bxf6
{ The only reasonable option for White.   10.Nxe7  ,  White gives up the central knight to create a structural weakness after ...Nxe7 Bxf6 gxf6, but Black is ready to play with the doubled pawns and seize the initiative. Compared to the line with 9.Bxf6, this is a better version for Black.  10...Nxe7  11.Bxf6  gxf6  looks similar to the Novosibirsk Variation, but the players have changed one more pair of minor pieces, which favors Black, who is ready to react in the center with ...f5 or ...d5.  12.c4  ,  since Black is ready to push ...d5, White tries to stop it by playing on the queenside.  As we will learn in the 9.Bxf6 chapter, Black can play  12...f5  here.  In this structure, every time White pushes the c-pawn, preparing Nc2, Black must play ...f5 no matter what!  13.exf5  Nxf5  ,  Black will put the knight on d4 soon.   10.Nxf6+?!  gxf6  − it may look strange to ruin the structure deliberately, but ...f5 is coming and Black gets a modest advantage.  11.Be3  f5!?  When this is possible, it is always the best choice.  12.exf5  d5  is the reason for the ...f5 push: conquering the center, particularly the crucial d5-square. Black will take on f5 later.  13.g3  ,  the best way to develop the bishop.  13...Bxf5  . }
10... Bxf6 11. c3
{ This is Sveshnikov's main line. Both  11.c3  and  11.c4  intend to bring the a3-knight into the game via c2, but there are essential differences. The pawn on c3 controls d4, which can be an outpost for the black knight, and leaves the door open to realize a breakthrough with a4, which is not good with the pawn on c4. We can say that the first option is more strategic, which is why it was the only one played in the past. Our predecessors strictly followed the general principles and rules, while today, we are used to thinking critically without having prejudices.   11.c4  ,  White forces Black to play ...b4; by doing that, White weakens d4.  11...b4  ,  Black rarely wants to capture on c4; remember that White is trying to dominate the light squares.  12.Nc2  ,  the knight retreat is almost forced.  12...O-O   I played both 12...O-O and 12...a5, and I wondered which one was more precise every time. It is often just a transposition, but ...O-O is more flexible. A critical line is  12...a5  13.Qf3  .  13.g3  is a popular continuation. White will go for Bg2 and then try to push f4.   13.Qf3  ,  as mentioned, Qf3 is crucial against 12...a5, but there's nothing to be afraid of in this move order.  13...Bg5  14.h4  Bh6  15.g4  ,  White threatens to trap the bishop.  15...f6  ,  with the castle included, White cannot go for g5 because after ...fxg5, the rook attacks the queen.  13...a5  ,  Black doesn't play ...Bg5 immediately to avoid the possible lines with h4.  14.Bg2  g6  is the second most popular choice. Since White intends to materialize the f4 break, Black prefers to put the bishop on g7 rather than g5. Many GMs played it, such as Pragg, Caruana, and Moiseenko.  15.Nxf6+  ,  White must eliminate the bishop before it is too late.  15...Qxf6  16.O-O  h5  and Black starts to attack the kingside. }
11... O-O 12. Nc2
{ Black has many common choices; my favorite is  12...Rb8  to prevent White's plan  with a4.  If  12...Bg5  , I suggest to my students to play  13.a4  for White, so I don't go for the most common move. }
12... Rb8 13. h4
{ This is the only annoying setup because it doesn't allow Black to put the bishop on the favorite square g5, but we have an alternative to the usual setup. White sets a little trap: ...Bxh4 loses to Qh5.   13.Be2  ,  these slow moves that don't directly act on the kingside @@StartBracket@@g3-h4@@EndBracket@@ or the queenside @@StartBracket@@a4@@EndBracket@@ are solid but not dangerous.  13...Bg5  14.O-O  and now there are several options for Black. In 2019, I played ...Kh8 inspired by Carlsen, but I got annoyed by Ncb4, so I concluded that it is preferable to avoid it by playing ...a5.  14...a5  15.Qd3  Ne7  is a key idea: eliminate the knight in the outpost. }
13... Be7
{ I also played  13...g6  and concluded that it is safer not to change the pawn structure. White wants to keep the dominance of d5 by playing Nce3, Qf3, and sometimes Bd3-c2-b3. }
14. Nce3 Be6 15. a4
{ Exploiting the fact that if  15...bxa4  ,  16.Qxa4  is good for White. }
15... Qd7
{ Black is not forced to capture and goes on with the standard setup. } 16. Be2
Bd8 17. axb5 axb5 18. h5 Bg5
{ This is not necessary, but I suggest preventing h6. This introduction presents only a short preview of what the course is about. You can start studying the theory now that you know the key ideas. I hope you will enjoy it! }
