[Black "6.Nde2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ This is the starting position of the Sveshnikov Sicilian. We are going to study now White's alternatives on move six. While in other Sicilian lines, such as the Najdorf, White has different options on the 6th move to fight for a slight advantage, in the Sveshnikov, the other lines besides the standard  6.Ndb5  , don't give Black any theoretical difficulty. These moves are all quite rare, and in my classic games, I've only experienced  6.Nde2  . }
6. Nde2
{ In their book Dangerous Weapons: The Sicilian, John Emms and Richard Palliser suggest playing this knight retreat. With the knight on e2, all Black's ideas to ruin the pawn structure by playing ...Bb4xc3 fade away.  The knight will soon be transferred to g3, from where it facilitates a kingside attack and usually provokes the ...g6 push. On the other hand, the knight blocks the normal development of the bishop on f1, so White loses a bit of time to castle. }
6... Bc5
{ Since c3 is well-protected, developing the bishop to c5 makes more sense, keeping an eye on f2. White must worry about ...Ng4 and ...Qb6. }
7. Ng3 d6
{ Never forget to fight against the opponent's ideas. White has control of the light squares, so ...d6 prevents the jump of the knight on f5 and threatens ...Ng4. This is a better version of the Sveshnikov usual setup; in all the lines with 6.Ndb5, Black gets the same structure, but the dark-squared bishop is passive on e7. }
8. Be2 { Covering the g4-square and preparing to castle. } 8... a6
{ This is not the most played, but it's an engine suggestion. In my game, I had many problems with the bishop on c5, so I can tell that it is better to free the a7-square as soon as possible and then continue with ...h6, ...O-O, and ...Be6.   8...Be6?!  9.O-O  h6  and here I was so worried  about Bg5 and Nd5 that I underestimated the idea of Na4.  10.Na4  Bb4  11.a3  Ba5  12.b4  Bc7  ½-½ Antolak-Gueci, EU-ch @@StartBracket@@Women@@EndBracket@@, Prague 2022. I lost so many tempi by moving the bishop and White gained space. This is the reason why I suggest playing 8...a6. }
9. O-O h6
{ This is an essential move to avoid problems on d5 with the Bg5 pin. } 10. Kh1
O-O 11. f4 exf4 12. Bxf4
{ Now that the e5-square is free, it is time to improve the knight on c6. }
12... Ne5
{ Both players have an isolated pawn. Black's king looks safer now, and the next moves are easy to find: ...Be6, ...Ng6, ...Rc8, ...Re8. The order of these moves can change depending on White's continuation. }
13. Nf5 Bxf5 14. exf5
{ After this exchange, d6 is the only isolated pawn, but it's well-protected and gives Black the strong square on e5 for the knight. }
14... Rc8 15. Nd5 Re8
{ White's structure is slightly superior, and White has the bishop pair, but Black controls the e- and the c-files, and our pieces are more coordinated. Both players have equal chances. }
