[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "6.Nb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ This is the starting position of the Sveshnikov Sicilian. We are going to study now White's alternatives on move six. While in other Sicilian lines, such as the Najdorf, White has different options on the 6th move to fight for a slight advantage, in the Sveshnikov, the other lines besides the standard  6.Ndb5  , don't give Black any theoretical difficulty. These moves are all quite rare, and in my classic games, I've only experienced  6.Nde2  . }
6. Nb3
{ This can be a common retreat in many lines of the Sicilian, but it makes sense only if Black has already played ...d6. Here, with the pawn still on d7, the bishop on f8 goes to b4 attacking the center and winning the battle for control of the d5-square. Moreover, Black can directly push the pawn to d5 without losing a tempo. }
6... Bb4 7. Bd3
{ The most popular choice: developing one more piece while defending the pawn on e4. }
7... d5 { On the first occasion, Black gets rid of the backward pawn. } 8. exd5
Nxd5 9. Bd2 { The most natural way to deal with the pressure on c3. } 9... Nxc3
{ Inflicting structural damage for free. } 10. bxc3 Bd6
{ The main line is  10...Be7  , but this move was chosen by Emmanuel Lasker against Schlechter in 1910, and the Correspondence Database agrees that it is the best choice. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Qh5 f5
{ A typical way to defend h7; now the g8-a2 diagonal is weaker, so Black has to put the king on h8 soon. }
13. f4 e4
{ With a supported passed pawn, every endgame will be an easy win for Black. }
14. Bc4+ Kh8 15. Be3 Bd7
{ Thanks to the pawn on e4, Black has a static advantage. We are ready to attack White's weaknesses on the c-file with ...Rc8 and ...Qc7. There are also assault prospects on the kingside with ...Rf6-h6. That means that Black is better. }
