[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ The starting position of the Sveshnikov Sicilian. } 6. Ndb5
{ White threatens Nd6+, gaining the bishop pair and control of the dark squares. Black is forced to play ...d6, when it will be harder to push the pawn to d5 in the future. }
6... d6
{ 6...h6  was played many times by the legendary GM Ulf Andersson.  Black allows the entry of the knight on d6.  7.Nd6+  Bxd6  8.Qxd6  Qe7  . How could one of the most famous strategists invent this line? The position seems terrible for Black; he gave up the bishop pair and will enter an endgame with the king  on e7. Even if I don't like it, it's perfectly playable.    9.Qxe7+  Kxe7  10.b3  d6  11.Ba3  a6  12.O-O-O  Rd8  13.Bc4  Be6  14.Bd5  Rac8  15.Kb2  b5  16.Bxc6  Rxc6  17.Rd3  Rb8  18.Nd5+  Bxd5  19.exd5  Rcc8  20.Bb4  Ra8  21.Ba5  g5  22.Re1  Nd7  23.h4  g4  24.f4  gxf3  25.gxf3  Rg8  26.f4  Rac8  27.fxe5  Nxe5  28.Bc3  f6  29.Re4  h5  30.Rd2  Rg4  31.Rde2  Rc5  32.Bxe5  dxe5  33.c4  bxc4  34.bxc4  Rxc4  35.Rxc4  Rxc4  0-1 Berg-Andersson, Katrineholm 1999. }
7. Be3 { Adding pressure on a7. } 7... a6
{ Black is always happy to chase the knight away from b5. } 8. Na3 Rb8
{ A fine prophylactic move, controlling b6, to make it difficult for the a3-knight to re-enter the game.   8...b5  9.Nd5  , White's idea is to enter into positions like 7.Nd5,  but with the target on b5.  9...Nxd5  10.exd5  Ne7  is playable but a worse version compared to Black's position after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nd5  . }
9. Nd5 Nxd5 10. exd5 Ne7
{ With the pawn on d5, Black has no strategic problems. The bishop on e3 can be attacked with ...Nf5 or ...f5. Black's idea is to complete development with ...g6, ...Bg7, and ...O-O, then start dynamic play on the kingside. }
11. c4 Nf5
{ The plan is a bit different than in the 7.Nd5 line because with the rook on b8, Black was forced to put the knight on e7. It makes sense to improve the position with ...Nf5, to annoy the white bishop, and to jump on d4 in the future. }
12. Bd2 Be7 13. Bd3 O-O 14. O-O Nh4
{ An aggressive move. Black has almost completed development and wants to push the pawn to f5 and activate the pawn majority on the kingside. }
15. Kh1 f5
{ White is too slow on the queenside, while Black can already attack the king on h1 or play in the center with ...e4. }
16. f3 Bd7 17. b4 Rc8
{ It's essential to stop the breakthrough with c5. The knight on a3 is useless, while Black can improve the position with ...Bf6 and ...Qe8-h5, so we are slightly better.   Also, the knight on h4 is a thorn in White's camp, and trying to get rid of it by  18.g3  would only make things worse:  18...Nxf3!  19.Qxf3  e4  , and if now  20.Bxe4  fxe4  21.Qxe4  Bh3  , Black's bishops will reign over the board. The position is already winning thanks to our active pieces. }
