1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5
{ If you remember well the first chapters, you already know that all the other moves, apart from  6.Ndb5  , are not critical. }
6... d6
{ The starting position of the theoretical discussions. We already went through  7.Nd5  and  7.Bg5  with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bxf6  , so we have to discuss @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nd5  , which can be divided into @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/5ppp/p1np1b2/1p1Np3/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.c3  and  11.c4  .   The critical square of every Sicilian is d5, and we can distinguish the structures where Black plays ...e6 or ...e5. Of course, the Sveshnikov is one of the openings where, by pushing the pawn to e5, Black creates a massive hole on d5, and White usually tries to occupy that with a piece. For these reasons,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  is the best option, trying to eliminate the only defender of  the d5-square and starting the fight for the center. }
7. Bg5 { Pinning the knight on f6. } 7... a6
{ It is essential to chase away the annoying knight on b5 and take space on the queenside. }
8. Na3
{ 8.Bxf6  gxf6  9.Na3  b5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bxf6  move order. }
8... b5
{ Black is threatening a fork with ...b4. Apart from  9.Bxf6  , White has only two options: the main line  9.Nd5  and the awkward  9.Nab1  . }
9. Nab1
{ This rare retreat is not recent. The first game in the Online Database was played in 1974. There's even a game between two legends: the former World Champion, Maia Chiburdanidze, and the best chess author of all times, GM Mark Dvoretsky, ended in a draw in 1978. The idea is to redeploy the terribly placed knight on a3. It was recently discussed on Twitter, so I think it can happen in games nowadays. People love to follow new trends, even though they are not the best choice. }
9... Be7 { Intending to push ...b4 if White allows it by not capturing on f6. }
10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. a4
{ The second purpose of Nab1 is to free the way for the a-pawn to start playing on the queenside. }
11... b4 { Of course, Black wants to limit White's actions. } 12. Nd5 Be6
{ Nepo delayed the castle, but it may be a transposition to the most played  12...O-O  . }
13. Bc4 { White forced Black to play ...b4 to get the c4-square. } 13... O-O
14. O-O Bg5
{ A typical move in the Sveshnikov. Black improves the bishop, controls the dark squares, and frees the queen from the defense of f6. }
15. Qd3 { Attacking a6. } 15... a5
{ Following the game Nasuta-Kuzubov 0-1 2019.  15...Kh8  16.Nd2  Bxd2  17.Qxd2  Qa5  18.c3  Qc5  19.Ba2  bxc3  20.bxc3  Na5  21.Rab1  h6  22.Rb4  Rab8  23.Qd3  Qa7  24.h3  Nb7  25.a5  Nc5  26.Qe2  Rb5  27.Rxb5  axb5  28.Qxb5  Rb8  29.Qe2  Qxa5  30.Bc4  Qa3  31.Qf3  Kh7  32.Re1  Qb2  33.Rd1  Ra8  34.Ne3  Ra1  35.Bxe6  fxe6  36.Nc4  Rxd1+  37.Qxd1  Qxc3  38.Nxd6  Nd3  39.Ne8  Qd4  40.Qe2  Nf4  41.Qc2  Qa1+  42.Kh2  Qf1  43.f3  h5  44.Nd6  Qe1  45.Nb5  h4  46.Nd6  Ne2  47.Qc5  Ng3  48.Qg1  Nf1+  49.Kh1  Qc1  50.Nb7  Ng3+  51.Kh2  Qf4  52.Qb1  Kh6  53.Kg1  Qd2  54.Kh2  Ne2  55.Qa1  Qf4+  56.Kh1  Ng3+  57.Kg1  Qe3+  58.Kh2  Qb6  59.Qc1+  Kh7  60.Nc5  Ne2  61.Qe1  Ng3  62.Nd3  Qb5  63.Nf2  Nf1+  64.Kg1  Ng3  65.Kh2  Nf1+  66.Kg1  Ng3  67.Kh2  ½-½ Giri-Nepomniachtchi, Bucharest 2023. }
16. c3
{ Many players reacted with ...Rb8, such as Harika Dronavalli against Eline Roebers in the recent World Cup, intending to fight for the b-file. But the rook stands better on c8. }
16... Rc8
{ GM Vidit's move. Black puts pressure on the c4-bishop and is ready to continue the game with ...g6 and ...f5 or ...bxc3 if White allows it. The position is balanced. }
