{ This is the main line in the Sveshnikov. Both  11.c3  and  11.c4  intend to bring  the a3-knight into the game via c2, but there are essential differences between the two moves. The pawn on c3 controls d4, which can be an outpost for the black knight. And leaves the door open to realize a breakthrough with a4, which is not good with the pawn on c4.  We can say that the first option is more strategic, which is why it was the only one played in the past. Our predecessors strictly followed the general principles and rules, while today, we are used to thinking critically without having prejudices. }
11... O-O 12. Nc2
{ Black has many common choices; my favorite is  12...Rb8  to prevent White's plan  with a4. If  12...Bg5  , I suggest to my students to play  13.a4  for White, so I don't go for the most common move.   12.Be2  Bg5  transposes to the 11.Be2 variation. }
12... Rb8 13. h4
{ This is the only annoying setup because it doesn't allow Black to put the bishop on our favorite square g5, but we have an alternative to the usual ensemble. White sets a little trap:  13...Bxh4  loses to  14.Qh5  . }
13... Be7
{ I also played  13...g6  and concluded that it is safer not to change the pawn structure. White wants to keep the dominance of d5 by playing Nce3, Qf3, and sometimes Bd3-c2-b3.   Once again, after  13...Bxh4??  14.Qh5  Bxf2+  15.Kxf2  h6-+  , White wins the bishop and the game. }
14. Nce3 Be6 15. a4
{ Exploiting the fact that if  15...bxa4  ,  16.Qxa4  is good for White.   15.Bd3  Qd7  would transpose to 14.Bd3. }
15... Qd7
{ Black is not forced to capture and goes on with the standard setup. } 16. Be2
{ 16.axb5  axb5  17.Be2  Bd8  and White cannot castle yet  because h4 would fall.  18.h5  Bg5  , transposing to the main line. }
16... Bd8 17. h5
{ This is the second choice in the Online Database, but it scores better than  17.axb5  axb5  , which transposes to the main line. }
17... Bg5 { It is not necessary, but I suggest preventing h6. } 18. axb5
{ Sooner or later, White has to take on b5. } 18... axb5 19. O-O Ne7
{ With the idea of ...Bxe3 and ...d5.  19...Rfd8  is much more played, but this is more coherent with the general plan. }
20. Qd3 h6
{ It is premature to capture e3; it is preferable to improve the position. }
21. Ra6 Bxe3 22. Nxe3 { Putting pressure on the backward pawn. } 22... d5
{ The typical breakthrough. For more details, see the corresponding chapter. }
