f4 h3
{ This is a rare occasion: Black prefers to keep the kingside closed and then try to make it on the queenside. }
19. Bh1 Nd4 20. Qd3
{ White's most wise continuation is to hold the tension as long as possible. }
20... a4 21. fxe5
{ When Black's intentions to advance on the queenside are clearer, White has to react on the center/kingside. }
21... Qxe5 22. Rad1 Nc6 23. Qxd6 Ra6
{ Yet another pawn sacrifice. Black reached a strategic dream: to conquer the e5-square and block the white bishop. This is what compensates for the material. }
24. Qxe5 Nxe5 25. Rd5 Re8 { Black must not move the knight for any reason. }
26. Rb5 Rd6 { Planning to enter the second rank. } 27. Nd5
{ After  27.Rxb4  Rd2  28.Rxa4  Rxb2  ,  the awful bishop on h1 gives Black total compensation for the two pawns. }
27... Ba6 28. Rxb4 Bxc4 29. Nf6+ { It seems that White wins material. } 29...
Rxf6 30. Rxf6 Rd8 { But Black has mating ideas. } 31. Bf3
{ White's vital move to stop ...Rd1+.  31.Rxa4??  Rd1+  32.Kf2  Rxh1  33.Rd6  Rxh2-+  and Black is winning. }
31... Kg7 32. Rf4 Rd2
{ This is not a forced line, but in the typical spirit of the Sveshnikov: Black sacrifices material to obtain the initiative. White must be cautious not to lose: the h-pawn is weak, the rook on f4 has no squares, and the king is paralyzed. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Structures & Ideas"]
[Black "Sveshnikov Structure 1 − Najdorf Type 2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/5ppp/p2p4/1p2p3/4P3/2P5/PP3PPP/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is the most common structure in the Sveshnikov Sicilian; it arises from the main line with 11.c3. Speaking about details, usually White has already captured the knight on f6 with the dark-squared bishop to take control of the d5-outpost, giving away the bishop pair; Black has already moved on the minority on the queenside and has forced a white knight on a3, which is misplaced.  Those two factors have something in common: Black's dark-squared bishop is going to g5 and is ready to be exchanged with the white knight to be repositioned to d5 via c2-e3. White's plan is strategic, playing for the d5-square and the backward pawn on d6. It is essential that after some trades, White wants to keep a piece on d5, not recapturing with the pawn; the ideal situation for White is the endgame with a good knight on d5 versus a terrible bishop on d8.  Compared with the Najdorf structure, White doesn't want to play on the kingside because opening the position with f4 only favors Black, which has the bishop pair, particularly the green bishop on the dark squares. On the other hand, Black's plan has to be very dynamic: a timely ...d5 break is always desirable because it will solve all the problems we spoke about; the ...f5 break is good when Black can use the central pawns and the power of the bishops, while it is bad if White manages to block the light squares and put a pair of pieces on e4 and d5.  Gaining some space on the queenside with ...a5 is always an improvement because it gives Black extra possibilities to open the position and get counterplay. When White plays a4 to weaken Black's queenside, the situation becomes double-edged because Black captures on a4 and can put pressure on the semi-open files, especially with a rook on b8. }
1... -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
