[White "Typical Structures & Ideas"]
[Black "Sveshnikov Structure 2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/5ppp/3p4/p3p3/1pP1P3/1P6/P4PPP/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This structure arises from the main line with 11.c4 b4. It is a permanent structure, so it's the most positional one in the opening. White fixed the structure on the queenside to get maximum control on the d5-square and put maximum pressure on the backward d6-pawn. On the other hand, Black gained space and can use the ...a5-a4 break to open the a-file and generate counterplay. Moreover, the dark squares are very weak, and Black can establish a strong piece on c5 or even d4, to block White's play.  In a position with opposite-colored bishops, the dark-squared one on Black's side will be extremely strong once it goes to the a7-g1 diagonal, while the light-squared bishop from White will be very passive.  Speaking about plans, we can have big differences compared to the other structures. For example, Black will never go for the ...f5 push because play is always focused on the queenside, and Black doesn't want at all to open the light squares for White; on the other hand, it is White that can do something on the kingside because the plan with h4-h5 can be annoying and also the f4 break can give a lot of play against Black's position.  White has a clear target on d6 and can double the major pieces to take it and sometimes look for some tactics with the c5 break, while Black is focused on the b3-pawn, which will be weak after ...a4xb3 and ...Ra3. A knight on c5 can be devastating for the pawn on b3, but a queen or bishop on c5 can be enough to hold the structure and continue playing on the open a-file. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Structures & Ideas"]
[Black "Sveshnikov Structure 3 − Najdorf Type 1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/pp3ppp/3p4/3Pp3/8/8/PPP2PPP/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is the typical structure that arises from the variation with 7.Nd5. We can see immediately that this exchange on d5 creates an unbalanced situation with a white majority on the queenside and a black majority on the kingside. It means that Black wants to directly attack White's king, pushing the pawns starting with ...f5, while on the other side of the board, White will push c4 and b4 to support the c5 break and create a powerful passed pawn.  Both colors can ignore what the opponent is doing and continue with their plan without defending or trying to stop the opponent's intentions, moving their structure to the weak side. In the first case, Black will be happy because play will land directly on the white king, so even if White captures some pawns and gets a crushing position on the queenside, will get mated. In the second case, let's see the plans to stop the opponent's initiative and how to react:  ♙Black blocks the queenside with ...a5 and ...b6, leaving White all the light squares. It's a good plan for Black once c4 has already been played by White. Suppose the white pawn is not on c4. In that case, White will use the f1-a6 diagonal to put a bishop on b5 or eventually on c6, the third rank to put a rook on c3 and eventually on c6, and the c4-square will be free for the knights that will attack all the black pawns.  ♙ White pushes f3 after f5. In my opinion, it's the best way to handle the position on the kingside because it doesn't give any contact point and leaves a flexible structure. For example, if Black pushes ...e4 after f3, White usually closes the position with f4 and obtains a significant advantage thanks to the d4-square and the free play on the other side. Against f3, Black can try to exchange the dark-squared bishop with ...Bg5 or use the g-pawn to open the file with ...g5-g4; sometimes Black can also temporarily fix the structure with ...f4, but only if White can't block on e4 and the ...e4 break then is unavoidable.  ♙ White pushes f4 after ...f5. It is important to notice that creating a passed pawn with ...e4 is often a mistake because it blocks the position where Black wants to attack and gives the d4-square for free. In this case, Black can take on f4 to get the e5-square for our pieces, use the three vs. two majority with ...g5 and ...f4, or keep the tension for some moves and later take on f4 under better conditions. }
1... -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Structures & Ideas"]
[Black "Sveshnikov Structure 4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/5p1p/p2p1p2/1p2p3/4P3/8/PPP2PPP/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is the most dynamic structure of the course because we reach it after White changes the dark-squared bishop on the f6-knight. This means that White wants to block the light squares and play versus the black dark-squared bishop, which usually goes to g7, while Black is ready to give up some pawns at any cost because the resulting open position will be perfect for our bishop pair.  Like all Sveshnikov's structures, White has the d5-square, and there is a backward pawn on d6, but this time, it can be different because Black's activity can destroy White's control. First of all, Black can sometimes lose the d6-pawn to gain some tempi  (we can also be faster in development and play against White's king in the center)  and open the dark squares for our bishop. Secondly, the ...f5 break can pulverize White's center and leave Black with three strong pawns that advance and squash White's pieces.  We can add that once Black crushes White's center, we will open up the position for our bishops and launch a strong attack on the kingside. Of course, White also has a bright side to the position: if White manages to control well the light squares, the f5-square can be used; additionally, White has the c4 push to take the initiative and increase the control on the d5-square so that Black has to sacrifice all the queenside pawns if Black wants to be fast and open the position in the center. If Black is not able to give space to the dark-squared bishop, White will have a strategically winning position. }
1. -- *

