[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a recurring situation in the Sveshnikov. Black expands on the kingside with ...f5, and White reacts with f4 to stop this attack. Thinking about candidate moves, we can capture on f4, push ...e4, or ignore the pawn.  Even though I knew this position, I made a mistake against GM Santos Ruiz and lost the game. The right choice is to capture on f4. Moreover, I like to say that there's a love story between the black knight and the e5-square. If you play ...e4, you lose control of this square irrevocably. }
1... exf4
{ Freeing e5 and creating an outpost on e4.   1...e4?  Closing the center favors White; here, in particular, we are leaving the d4-square for all of White's pieces while our knight cannot jump to e5, and the structure blocks the bishop on c8. }
2. Bxf4 Nc5
{ The knight is going to e4 now instead of e5 because it is an outpost, and the majority on the kingside can be pushed with ...g5 and ...f4. }
*

