[Black "Big pawn center with ...f5 and ...d5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/4qpbp/p2p1p2/1p2p3/2P1P3/N2B4/PP3PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... f5
{ The typical central break opens the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop and creates dynamism. }
2. cxb5
{ 2.exf5?!  e4  generates the thematic tactics you can find at the end of the theoretical section. }
2... d5
{ It is rare to find opening lines where one player has three central pawns versus one. As you will master during the whole course, Black sacrifices the b- and d-pawns to obtain a majority in the middle of the board. }
3. bxa6
{ After  3.exd5  e4  4.Be2  Bxb2  ,  Black takes back one pawn and is ready to assault the white king.  5.Nc4  Qb4+  ,  forcing the knight retreat.  6.Nd2  axb5∓  ,  Black prefers not to capture on a1 because we can also have problems with the dark squares. The rook's relative value is much lower than the bishop's.   3.exf5?  is even worse than exd5 because Black can regain the f5-pawn very soon, and the pawns on e5 and d5 are stronger than f5 and e5.  3...Qb4+  4.Qd2  Qxd2+  5.Kxd2  e4-+  ,  with a winning pre-endgame. }
3... O-O
{ Don't forget about the king's safety. Now that the e8-a4 diagonal is open, it is better to castle before playing in the center. }
4. O-O fxe4 5. Bb5 Rd8
{ Black will equalize material with ...Bxa6, and thanks to the bishop pair, the 'big pawn center' has a considerable advantage. }
