{ This is similar to the previous example, with the difference of White's fianchetto. It may seem wild to sacrifice a pawn and open the long white diagonal, but ...d5 is rarely wrong in the Sveshnikov. }
1... d5 2. c3
{ 2.Qxd5  Rb8  3.O-O  O-O  4.Qd3  Bg4  ,  incredibly, Black should lose the pawn on d6 rather than keep it.   2.exd5  Qb4+  3.c3  Qxb2⩱  ,  Black takes back the pawn and forces some complications that we will deeply cover in the 9.Bxf6 chapter. }
2... dxe4 3. Bxe4 Rb8 { ...f5 is coming next. } 4. Nc2 f5 5. Bc6+ Kf8
{ The king is safe thanks to the pawns and Black is fine. } *

