Bxe4 d5
{ As they say, 'Good things come in three'. Black deflects the white bishop from the defense of f5. }
5. Bxd5 Rb8
{ Black has three pawns less but will capture f5 and b2 almost forcedly, and activity matters more than material count. As I usually repeat, it is better not to play the Sveshnikov if you care about your pawns. }
6. Rad1 Bxb2 7. Nc2 Bxf5 { Gaining important developing tempi. } 8. Ne3 Bh3 9.
Rfe1 Bc3 10. Re2 Rfc8
{ Black has total compensation for the pawn thanks to the bishop pair. The sacrifices opened the position in our favor. }
