{ Not only did Black open the position for the bishop pair but now also plays against the dominated white knight. Thanks to the b5-pawn, it has no squares.  This is a valuable example of the so-called 'green bishop', a definition I learned from GM Karsten Müller. It is the bishop that the opponent doesn't have, and the side with the bishop pair should try to open it as much as possible by placing the pawns on squares of the opposite color. As you may have noticed, Black's pawns are all on the light squares. }
