[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) 6th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "6.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ This is the starting position of the Sveshnikov Sicilian. We are going to study now White's alternatives on move six. While in other Sicilian lines, such as the Najdorf, White has different options on the 6th move to fight for a slight advantage, in the Sveshnikov, the other lines besides the standard  6.Ndb5  , don't give Black any theoretical difficulty. These moves are all quite rare, and in my classic games, I've only experienced  6.Nde2  . }
6. Nf3 { A passive continuation that leaves the initiative in Black's hands. }
6... Bb4
{ Black reacts in the same way as the line with Nb3; b4 is the best square for the bishop. What is the difference between the knight on b3 and the knight on f3? On f3, it blocks White's f2-f4 push, but it defends the king better and is closer to Black's castle. }
7. Bd2
{ Unfortunately for White, it looks like a good move but loses material. } 7...
Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Nxe4 { The start of some complications. } 9. Nxe5
{ In the Online Database,  9.Nxe5  and  9...Nxc3  are equally played, but taking the bishop to compromise White's structure is better. }
9... Nxc3 10. Nxc6
{ 10.bxc3??  Nxe5-+  and Black remains with an extra piece. } 10... Nxd1 11.
Nxd8 Nxb2
{ The difference between the two knights is clear: the one on d8 is trapped. }
12. Nxb7 Bxb7 13. Rb1 { Can Black keep the extra pawn? } 13... Bxg2
{ Yes, with this intermediate move, Black keeps the advantage. } 14. Bxg2 Rb8
{ The knight is defended, the king is ready to castle, and Black can try to convert the extra pawn into a win. }
