[Black "6.Nf3 #2 | Informational 7...Nxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ This is the starting position of the Sveshnikov Sicilian. We are going to study now White's alternatives on move six. While in other Sicilian lines, such as the Najdorf, White has different options on the 6th move to fight for a slight advantage, in the Sveshnikov, the other lines besides the standard  6.Ndb5  , don't give Black any theoretical difficulty. These moves are all quite rare, and in my classic games, I've only experienced  6.Nde2  . }
6. Nf3 { A passive continuation that leaves the initiative in Black's hands. }
6... Bb4
{ Black reacts in the same way as the line with Nb3; b4 is the best square for the bishop. What is the difference between the knight on b3 and the knight on f3? On f3, it blocks White's f2-f4 push, but it defends the king better and is closer to Black's castle. }
7. Bc4
{ The idea is to sacrifice a pawn to get the bishop pair and control the dark squares, but probably, it won't be enough to equalize the position. }
7... Nxe4 8. Qd5
{ More precise than  8.Bxf7+  . Let's see what happens if White plays like in the 'twin' line with 6.Nb3.  8...Kxf7  9.Qd5+  Ke8  10.Qxe4  d5  .  With the knight on f3 instead of b3, the queen can't go to d3 because of the fork on e4.  11.Qe2   11.Qd3?  e4  12.Qe3  Kf7!  It's a weird-looking move but strong and with a clear plan: unpin the pawn and if possible, castle by hand with ...Re8 and ...Kg8.  13.Ng5+  Kg8  14.a3  Be7∓  . Now the king is safer, and Black has a good advantage thanks to the bishop pair and the central  pawns on e4 and d5.  11...Bg4  ,  another move that is not possible with the knight on b3.  12.h3  Bxf3  13.Qxf3  d4  14.a3  ,  the critical move to save the piece on c3.  14...Qa5  , with a double pin!  15.Rb1!  dxc3  16.axb4  Qa2  , when I think every human player with White would feel in a losing position while the engine manages to save everything.  17.O-O!  Sacrificing a rook!  17...Qxb1  18.Qd5  , White's idea is to look for a perpetual check or to exploit the almost trapped queen  on b1.  18...Qxc2  19.Qe6+  Kd8  , escaping from checks.   20.b5!  A computer move to drive away a defender.  20...Qg6  , exchanging pieces would favor Black because of material advantage.  21.Rd1+  Kc7  22.Qd7+  Kb8  23.bxc6  Qxc6  , Black managed to avoid a draw and secure the king.  24.Qxg7  Re8⩱  is the end of this crazy and almost forced line. According to the engine, the evaluation is equal, but Black has a rook against the inactive bishop  on c1, and I believe the chances of victory are high. }
8... Nd6 9. Bb3 O-O 10. O-O Ne8
{ Redirecting the knight to f6; there was no way to save the pawn on e5 without giving all the initiative. }
11. Nxe5 Nf6 12. Qb5
{ White doesn't want to make a draw with the forced  12.Nxf7  . What a nice move!  Opening the diagonal for the bishop on b3.  12...Qe7  ,  the knight on f7 looks scary but has no good squares to attack Black's pieces with a discovered check.   12...Nxd5??  13.Nxd8  and  Black loses material because of the pin of the knight on d5.  13...Bxc3  14.Bxd5+  Kh8  15.Nf7+  Kg8  16.Nd6+  Kh8  17.bxc3+–  , White is winning because of the material advantage.  13.Nh6+  Kh8  14.Nf7+  Kg8=  and there's nothing more than a perpetual check. }
12... Bxc3 13. bxc3 a6
{ The queen has few squares, and White narrowly survives. } 14. Qc5 d6 15. Nxc6
{ Solving the problem by exchanging the pieces. } 15... dxc5 16. Nxd8 Rxd8
{ In this endgame, both players have equal chances. White has the bishop pair, but the structure is worse, and Black controls the d-file. }
