1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ This is the starting position of the Sveshnikov Sicilian. We are going to study now White's alternatives on move six. While in other Sicilian lines, such as the Najdorf, White has different options on the 6th move to fight for a slight advantage, in the Sveshnikov, the other lines besides the standard  6.Ndb5  , don't give Black any theoretical difficulty. These moves are all quite rare, and in my classic games, I've only experienced  6.Nde2  . }
6. Nb3
{ This can be a common retreat in many lines of the Sicilian, but it makes sense only if Black has already played ...d6. Here, with the pawn still on d7, the bishop on f8 goes to b4 attacking the center and winning the battle for control of the d5-square. Moreover, Black can directly push the pawn to d5 without losing a tempo. }
6... Bb4 7. Bc4 { A tricky move. } 7... O-O
{ 7...Nxe4?!  8.Bxf7+!?  Always pay attention to the opponent's ideas!  8...Kxf7  9.Qd5+  , with a double attack. White takes back the piece and can exploit the loneliness of Black's king.  9...Ke8  10.Qxe4  d5  , occupying the center and looking  forward to playing ...d4. But is Black gaining material on c3?  11.Qe2  d4  12.a3!  is a typical way to solve the pin. Unfortunately, there's nothing for Black. After  12...Be7  13.Ne4  Bf5=  , the position would be great if Black could castle, but we have moved the king already. }
8. O-O Bxc3
{ Once again, giving the bishop pair to weaken White's pawn structure. } 9.
bxc3 Nxe4
{ This can be considered a gambit − the bishop pair in such an open position can give White a small compensation but nothing more. }
10. Ba3 d6 11. Qd3 { Now it's better to give back the pawn. } 11... Nf6 12.
Qxd6 Qxd6
{ In a potential endgame, it would be easy for Black to exploit the opponent's weaknesses. }
13. Bxd6 Rd8 14. Ba3 Bf5 { Black is the only one who can play for the win. } *

