1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ This is the starting position of the Sveshnikov Sicilian. We are going to study now White's alternatives on move six. While in other Sicilian lines, such as the Najdorf, White has different options on the 6th move to fight for a slight advantage, in the Sveshnikov, the other lines besides the standard  6.Ndb5  , don't give Black any theoretical difficulty. These moves are all quite rare, and in my classic games, I've only experienced  6.Nde2  . }
6. Nb3
{ This can be a common retreat in many lines of the Sicilian, but it makes sense only if Black has already played ...d6. Here, with the pawn still on d7, the bishop on f8 goes to b4 attacking the center and winning the battle for control of the d5-square. Moreover, Black can directly push the pawn to d5 without losing a tempo. }
6... Bb4 7. Bd2
{ Unpinning the knight and avoiding the creation of doubled pawns after ...Bxc3. }
7... O-O
{ The second choice in the Online Database. We prefer to avoid complicated lines, it's easier to continue by developing, and as they say, 'the threat is stronger than the execution'! }
8. Bd3 d5
{ Forcing White to exchange in view of ...Bxc3 and ...dxe4.   The strategic  8...Bxc3  exchange looks good, but it is less effective now  that e4 is well-defended.  9.Bxc3  d5  , White opens up the position, and the bishop pair becomes strong.  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Qd2!?  a5↑  . When the opponent has a knight in the corner, it is often a good idea to attack it by pushing the pawn. The engine is quite happy for Black, but I believe that the rising position after 8...d5 is more enjoyable from a human point of view. }
9. exd5
{ 9.Nxd5  doesn't change the story. After  9...Nxd5  10.exd5  Qxd5  , it's the same position. }
9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 { Centralizing the queen and hitting the g2-pawn. } 11.
Bxb4 Qxg2 { A nice intermediate move. } 12. Rf1 Nxb4
{ Not only has Black gained a pawn but also destroyed every possibility for White to castle. }
