{ This can be a common retreat in many lines of the Sicilian, but it makes sense only if Black has already played ...d6. Here, with the pawn still on d7, the bishop on f8 goes to b4 attacking the center and winning the battle for control of the d5-square. Moreover, Black can directly push the pawn to d5 without losing a tempo. }
6... Bb4 7. Bd3
{ The most popular choice: developing one more piece while defending the pawn on e4. }
7... d5 { On the first occasion, Black gets rid of the backward pawn. } 8. exd5
Nxd5 9. Bd2 { The most natural way to deal with the pressure on c3. } 9... Nxc3
{ Inflicting structural damage for free. } 10. bxc3 Bd6
{ The main line is  10...Be7  , but this move was chosen by Emmanuel Lasker against Schlechter in 1910, and the Correspondence Database agrees that it is the best choice. }
11. Qh5 { Preventing Black's castle. } 11... g6
{ My students fear moving the g-pawn because it weakens the king's position, but here, it's the only way to manage castling in the future. }
12. Qh6 Bf8 13. Qe3 Bg7
{ Black's king will be super safe on g8 with the fianchettoed bishop. } *

