9. f3 Be6 10. Be3 { This is considered dubious due to  10...Nb4  . } 10... Nb4
{ Preparing ...d5. } 11. Nc4 d5 12. Bb6 Qe7
{ I believe it would be hard to play ...Qe7 without knowing it. It seems that the queen blocks the bishop on f8, and it is not the ideal square, but it's the only way to avoid a potential double attack with Nb6 in the future. }
13. exd5 Nbxd5
{ It's better to take on d5 with the knight on b4 so that the knight on f6 protects the e4-square.   For example, after  13...Nfxd5?  14.Ne4  , we have a problem  on d6. White is already taking over, as c3 is also a threat. }
14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bf2 Rd8
{ Black's pieces are in the center; the queen will move to c7 to free the e7-square for the bishop. Then Black will castle and play on the kingside with ...Nf4. }
