{ This move scores better than  8...Be6  . The idea is to  provoke f3 before returning to e6. Black wishes to carry out ...d5, and ...Bg4 is an excellent way to help the plan. }
9. f3 Be6 10. Bg5 Be7 { The most natural way to solve the pin on the knight. }
11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Bc4
{ From a strategic point of view, White is happy to exchange the light-squared bishop to eliminate the only defender of the d5-square. But Black is not forced to take on c4 and is not afraid to take on e6 with the pawn. If you want to play the Sveshikov, you must be ready to double your pawns on e5 and e6 to control d5. }
12... O-O 13. Bxe6 fxe6
{ Black is always happy to have this structure; e6 is not a weakness and stops the knight's jump on d5. }
