13. Nb6
{ 13.Nxd6+?  Bxd6  14.Qxd6  Nxc2+  15.Kf2  Nxa1-+  , winning a rook and the game. }
13... Rc5 { Fighting for d5. } 14. a5 d5 { An interesting sacrifice. } 15. exd5
Bf5 { Attacking c2. } 16. Rc1 Qh6
{ White's pieces are not coordinated, and Black is ready to exploit the position of the king on e1 by playing ...Qh4+ or ...Qe3+. }
17. h4 Be7 18. g3 e4
{ Opening up the e-file against the opponent's king. Black is ready to castle and has more than sufficient compensation for the pawn.   Preventing the queen's entrance to e3 with  19.f4  doesn't improve White's structure much. After  19...O-O  , finishing development is problematic for White. For instance,  20.Bg2  Qg6  highlights the  weak pawn on g3, which cannot be protected by  21.Kf2  due to  21...Rxc3!  followed by ...Bc5+ and ...Qxg3, with a ravishing attack. }
