10... Rc8 11. O-O Nb4
{ A key move in these lines, fighting for the d5-square. } 12. Qe2
{ The engine's suggestion. } 12... Qc7 { Adding more pressure on c4. } 13. b3
d5 { Once again, Black manages to push the pawn to d5. } 14. exd5
{ 14.Nxd5  Nbxd5  15.exd5  Nxd5=  transposes to the 14.exd5 move order. } 14...
Nbxd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Kh1
{ A prophylactic move. Playing  16.f4  first runs into  16...exf4  17.Bxd5  Qc5+  followed by ...Qxd5, with a preferable position for Black. }
16... Bc5
{ 16...Bb4  instead allows some trickery with  17.Nb5  , when the knight is taboo:  17...axb5?  18.Bxd5  Bxd5  19.Qxb5+  and the bishop drops. }
17. f4 { 17.Bb2  O-O  transposes to the 16.Bb2 variation. } 17... O-O 18. f5
{ White's only alternative to fight for equality, trying to remove the defender of the strong knight on d5. Now Black must find an essential intermediate move. }
18... Nc3 { Only move. } 19. Qf3 Bxc4 20. Nxc4
{ A critical moment. Is Qxc3 a threat or not? Luckily for Black, it isn't! }
20... b5 { Counterattacking the opponent's knight. } 21. Qxc3 Bd4 22. Qg3
{ The only move if White doesn't want to lose. } 22... Bxa1 23. f6 g6 24. Qg5
{ White is threatening mate in 2, so Black needs to be careful. } 24... e4
{ Another only move. } 25. axb5 axb5 26. Bf4 Qa7 27. Be3
{ White has to find some difficult resources. } 27... Qa6 28. Nb6 Rcd8
{ A highly complex position: Black gained the exchange, but White has total compensation thanks to the strong pawn on f6 and the mating ideas on the dark squares. It's approximately equal. }
