{ This was played for the first time in 1910 against Lasker. White wants to prevent ...b5 and is ready to meet  7...a6  with  8.Na3  followed by Nc4. The negative side of this move is that a4 is not contributing to the fight for the d5-square, so Black can try to get counterplay in the center. }
7... a6 8. Na3 Bg4
{ This move scores better than  8...Be6  . The idea is to  provoke f3 before returning to e6. Black wishes to carry out ...d5, and ...Bg4 is an excellent way to help the plan. }
9. f3 Be6 10. Bc4
{ White prevents Black from carrying out ...d5, but the disadvantage is that the a3-knight cannot re-enter play. }
