[Black "Alternative 8...Be6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ The starting position of the Sveshnikov Sicilian. } 6. Ndb5
{ White threatens Nd6+, gaining the bishop pair and control of the dark squares. Black is forced to play ...d6, when it will be harder to push the pawn to d5 in the future. }
6... d6
{ 6...h6  was played many times by the legendary GM Ulf Andersson.  Black allows the entry of the knight on d6.  7.Nd6+  Bxd6  8.Qxd6  Qe7  . How could one of the most famous strategists invent this line? The position seems terrible for Black; he gave up the bishop pair and will enter an endgame with the king  on e7. Even if I don't like it, it's perfectly playable.    9.Qxe7+  Kxe7  10.b3  d6  11.Ba3  a6  12.O-O-O  Rd8  13.Bc4  Be6  14.Bd5  Rac8  15.Kb2  b5  16.Bxc6  Rxc6  17.Rd3  Rb8  18.Nd5+  Bxd5  19.exd5  Rcc8  20.Bb4  Ra8  21.Ba5  g5  22.Re1  Nd7  23.h4  g4  24.f4  gxf3  25.gxf3  Rg8  26.f4  Rac8  27.fxe5  Nxe5  28.Bc3  f6  29.Re4  h5  30.Rd2  Rg4  31.Rde2  Rc5  32.Bxe5  dxe5  33.c4  bxc4  34.bxc4  Rxc4  35.Rxc4  Rxc4  0-1 Berg-Andersson, Katrineholm 1999. }
7. a4
{ This was played for the first time in 1910 against Lasker. White wants to prevent ...b5 and is ready to meet  7...a6  with  8.Na3  followed by Nc4. The negative side of this move is that a4 is not contributing to the fight for the d5-square, so Black can try to get counterplay in the center. }
7... a6 8. Na3 Be6 { The first choice in the Online Database. } 9. Bg5 Qb6
{ An interesting resource. With the bishop on e6, Nc4 is not a problem, and the black queen can be developed. This is the first time I have seen this idea in the Sveshnikov, and I believe that the difference with the usual lines is that White has poor control of the light squares on c4 and d5, so b6 cannot be attacked. }
10. Nc4 Qb4 { Of course, Black doesn't want to give up the bishop. } 11. Bxf6
Bxc4 { A novelty in this position. } 12. Bg5 Nd4
{ It will be hard for White to castle, and Black has a lot of activity in the center.   12...Qxb2?!  Don't be too greedy; a pawn is not worth development tempi. Following  13.Bd2  Bxf1  14.Rb1  Qa3  15.Kxf1  Rb8  , White is slightly better despite  having the king on f1. The rook on b1 is excellent, and Black must lose other moves to return with the queen. }
