7. a4
{ This was played for the first time in 1910 against Lasker. White wants to prevent ...b5 and is ready to meet  7...a6  with  8.Na3  followed by Nc4. The negative side of this move is that a4 is not contributing to the fight for the d5-square, so Black can try to get counterplay in the center. }
7... a6 8. Na3 Be6 { The first choice in the Online Database. } 9. Bg5 Qb6
{ An interesting resource. With the bishop on e6, Nc4 is not a problem, and the black queen can be developed. This is the first time I have seen this idea in the Sveshnikov, and I believe that the difference with the usual lines is that White has poor control of the light squares on c4 and d5, so b6 cannot be attacked. }
10. Rb1 Qb4
{ The main idea of ...Qb6 − now e4, is a target. It reminds me of a similar plan invented by Tal in the Benoni. }
11. Bxf6 { Removing an attacker. } 11... gxf6
{ Black is not afraid to ruin the pawn structure. The doubled pawns cannot be attacked easily by White. }
12. Bd3 d5
{ Black can be more than satisfied in this position: bishop pair in an open position, the ...d5 break is in, and White has to solve the problems with the knight on c3 and the e4-pawn. }
