[Black "Modern Main Line 7.Nd5 − 9.Qf3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ The starting position of the Sveshnikov Sicilian. } 6. Ndb5
{ White threatens Nd6+, gaining the bishop pair and control of the dark squares. Black is forced to play ...d6, when it will be harder to push the pawn to d5 in the future. }
6... d6
{ 6...h6  was played many times by the legendary GM Ulf Andersson.  Black allows the entry of the knight on d6.  7.Nd6+  Bxd6  8.Qxd6  Qe7  . How could one of the most famous strategists invent this line? The position seems terrible for Black; he gave up the bishop pair and will enter an endgame with the king  on e7. Even if I don't like it, it's perfectly playable.    9.Qxe7+  Kxe7  10.b3  d6  11.Ba3  a6  12.O-O-O  Rd8  13.Bc4  Be6  14.Bd5  Rac8  15.Kb2  b5  16.Bxc6  Rxc6  17.Rd3  Rb8  18.Nd5+  Bxd5  19.exd5  Rcc8  20.Bb4  Ra8  21.Ba5  g5  22.Re1  Nd7  23.h4  g4  24.f4  gxf3  25.gxf3  Rg8  26.f4  Rac8  27.fxe5  Nxe5  28.Bc3  f6  29.Re4  h5  30.Rd2  Rg4  31.Rde2  Rc5  32.Bxe5  dxe5  33.c4  bxc4  34.bxc4  Rxc4  35.Rxc4  Rxc4  0-1 Berg-Andersson, Katrineholm 1999. }
7. Nd5
{ In my opinion, this is the best option for White. The main line with  7.Bg5  looks more natural, and, honestly, it was the only move I knew for White when I became WFM. But after four years of playing only Sveshnikov with Black, I can say that my most vigorous opponents played  mostly Nd5. It probably became more popular since Fabiano Caruana played it four times against Magnus Carlsen during the World Championship Match 2018.  Is White losing a tempo and violating the opening principle 'don't move the same piece twice'? The threat is Nc7+, so Black is forced to take on d5, and after exd5, it is Black's turn to lose a tempo with the knight on c6. }
7... Nxd5
{ Everyone knows that, if possible, White wants to take with a piece on d5. So why is exd5 the most-played move? }
8. exd5
{ We obtained the structure that GM Mauricio Flores Rios calls Najdorf type 1 in his book Chess Structures. But why are we talking about Najdorf if this is a Sveshnikov course? The structure is the same, so let's call it 'Sveshnikov's structure 3'.  White has a majority on the queenside and plans to advance with b4, c4, and then c5. On the other hand, Black has the activity on the kingside and will play ...f5 and create an attack against White's king. Black often frees play by exchanging the dark-squared bishops via g5 or even h4, which will facilitate attacking maneuvers such as ...Rf8-f6-h6. }
8... Nb8
{ Moving back to the initial square, the knight will go to d7 soon, controlling c5. }
9. Qf3
{ A tricky move; the idea is to attack the pawn on d6 by playing Qa3 and then Bd2-b4. }
9... a6 10. Qa3
{ Exploiting the pin on the a6-pawn and putting pressure on d6. } 10... Be7
{ Now White has a choice between the natural Bd2 and the shocking Bg5.  10...axb5??  11.Qxa8+-  , gaining material. }
11. Bg5
{ Imagine the face of someone who has never seen this idea and has to deal with it over the board! }
11... f6 { An ugly but safe move.  11...Bxg5?  loses at once. } 12. Bd2 O-O 13.
Bb4 { Adding pressure on d6. } 13... Qd7 14. Nxd6
{ White cannot go hunting pawns before finishing development without being punished! }
14... a5 15. Bc5 b6 { Removing a defender. } 16. Bb5 Qc7 17. Nxc8 Bxc5 18. Qb3
Qxc8 { Winning a piece and the game. } *

