{ We obtained the structure that GM Mauricio Flores Rios calls Najdorf type 1 in his book Chess Structures. But why are we talking about Najdorf if this is a Sveshnikov course? The structure is the same, so let's call it 'Sveshnikov's structure 3'.  White has a majority on the queenside and plans to advance with b4, c4, and then c5. On the other hand, Black has the activity on the kingside and will play ...f5 and create an attack against White's king. Black often frees play by exchanging the dark-squared bishops via g5 or even h4, which will facilitate attacking maneuvers such as ...Rf8-f6-h6. }
8... Nb8
{ Moving back to the initial square, the knight will go to d7 soon, controlling c5. }
9. a4
{ Preparing to transfer the knight to c4 via a3 and preventing Black's plan with ...b5. }
9... Be7 { Preparing to castle. } 10. Bd2
{ Generally, Bd2 is played to support a5 and b4 or to put the bishop on b4 where it attacks d6. Many GMs played Bd2, but we can say that Nepomniatchtchi is the one who introduced it. }
10... O-O 11. a5
{ The second most played move in the Online Database, but it's Nepo's favorite. }
11... Nd7
{ With the pawn on a5, the knight must stay on d7 to protect the b6-square. }
12. Bb4
{ In this position, Nakamura played  12.a6  , but the engine suggests an interesting  12...e4! }
12... e4
{ Played by FM Eswaran at the USA Women's Championship in 2022. White is behind in development, so Black has to activate the pieces at full speed. With this move, we open the diagonal for the bishop heading to f6, and we free the e5-square for our knight. Moreover, the ...e3 push can leave White’s king exposed.   12...a6  13.Na3  f5  14.Nc4  Nf6  15.Nb6  Rb8  16.Ra3  f4□  17.Be2  Bf5  18.O-O  Qe8  19.c4  Qg6  20.Kh1  Rbd8  21.f3  Nh5  22.Bd3  Ng3+  23.Kg1  Nxf1  24.Bxf5  Qxf5  25.Qxf1  e4  26.Bc3  exf3  0-1 Nepomniachtchi-Nakamura, Speed chess.com blitz 2019. }
13. Bxd6 { For sure, the most critical line. } 13... Bxd6 14. Nxd6 Nf6
{ Attacking the knight and the pawn with an x-ray. } 15. Nxc8 Rxc8
{ Megan Lee went for c4, trying to keep alive the d5-pawn. } 16. c4 b5
{ An amazing move! Black is trying to remove the defender and destroy White's center. }
17. axb6 Qxb6 18. Be2
{ The only move for White, who has to castle as soon as possible. } 18... e3
{ Seizing the initiative. } 19. f3 Qb4+ 20. Kf1 Qxb2
{ I think this position is hard for White with the king on f1 and the heavy pieces that cannot communicate. White has a strong center, but Black is more developed and has good counterplay. For these reasons, the position is approximately equal. }
*

