{ The best choice in correspondence chess. It was also played in the World Championship match between Caruana and Carlsen in 2018. }
12... a6
{ I prefer this move rather than Carlsen's  12...f5  ,  to play 13...a5 and avoid a5 from White.   12...f5  13.a5  a6  14.Na3  e4  15.Nc4  Ne5  16.Nb6  Rb8  17.f4  exf3  18.Bxf3  g5  19.c4  f4  20.Bc3  Bf5  21.c5  Nxf3+  22.Qxf3  dxc5  23.Rad1  Bd6  24.h3  Qe8  25.Nc4  Qg6  26.Nxd6  Qxd6  27.h4  gxh4  28.Qxf4  Qxf4  29.Rxf4  h5  30.Re1  Bg4  31.Rf6  Rxf6  32.Bxf6  Kf7  33.Bxh4  Re8  34.Rf1+  Kg8  35.Rf6  Re2  36.Rg6+  Kf8  37.d6  Rd2  38.Rg5  ½-½ Caruana-Carlsen, London 2018. }
13. Na3 a5
{ Black does not lose a tempo with the pawn because the knight is forced to go back. This is a typical theme in the a4 lines of the Sveshnikov. }
14. Nb5
{ With this move, I lost against an IM, and he told me he was following the game Abdusattorov-Aryan 2022. }
14... f5 15. b4
{ Forcing Black to make essential decisions on the queenside. Would you take on b4 or play the passive ...b6? During the game, it was a Hamletic doubt for me.   15.f4  was seen in ½-½ Sevian-Swiercz, USA-ch rapid 2020. After  15...Nf6  16.Kh1  Ne4  17.Be3  exf4  18.Bxf4  Bd7  19.Bd3  Bxb5  20.axb5  Bg5  21.Qc1  Bxf4  22.Qxf4  Qe7  ,  the outpost on e4 for our knight is great, White's king is a little bit weaker, and White's pawn majority on the queenside is blocked. In general, I think that Black should be slightly better.    23.Rae1  Rae8  24.Re2  Qe5  25.Qxe5  Rxe5  26.Kg1  g6  27.Bxe4  fxe4  28.Rxf8+  Kxf8  29.c4  e3  30.b3  Re4  31.Kf1  a4  32.bxa4  Rxc4  33.Ra2  Rc5  34.Ke2  Ke7  35.Kxe3  Rxd5  36.Rc2  Kd7  37.Ke4  Rh5  38.g3  Re5+  39.Kd4  h5  40.Rf2  Ke7  41.Rf3  b6  42.Rb3  Kd7  43.Rc3  Re1  44.Rc6  Rd1+  45.Ke4  Re1+  46.Kf4  Ra1  47.Rc4  d5  48.Rc6  Rxa4+  49.Ke5  h4  50.Rxg6  hxg3  51.hxg3  Rb4  52.Rxb6  Rg4  53.Rb7+  Kc8  54.Rh7  Rxg3  55.Kxd5  Rg5+  56.Kc6  Rg6+  57.Kc5  Kb8  58.Rd7  Rh6  59.Rd6  Rxd6  60.Kxd6  Kb7  61.Kc5  Kc7  62.b6+  Kb7  63.Kb5  Kb8  64.Ka6  Ka8  65.b7+  Kb8  66.Kb6  ½-½ Sevian-Swiercz, USA-ch rapid 2020. }
15... axb4
{ Ultimately, I went for  15...b6  ,  so I suggest you take on b4!  16.c4  axb4  17.Bxb4  Rf6  is not the best move; the engine prefers ...Nc5, but I wanted to lift the rook and create attacking opportunities.  18.Ra3  Rh6  19.Qa1  Bf8  20.a5  bxa5  21.Rxa5  Rxa5  22.Qxa5  Qh4  23.h3  Rg6  24.Qa3  Qg5  25.g3  Qh6  26.Kg2  e4  27.f4  exf3+  28.Qxf3  Rf6  29.Qf4  g5  30.Qd4  Rf7  31.Na7  Bb7  32.Nc6  Nc5  33.Qe3  f4  34.Qe8  Qg7  35.Bh5  Rc7  36.Ba5  Rc8  37.Nd8  h6  38.gxf4  Nd7  39.Qf7+  Kh8  40.Qxg7+  Bxg7  41.Nxb7  Rxc4  42.f5  Be5  43.Bf3  Ra4  44.Bd2  Kg7  45.Nd8  Kf6  46.Nc6  Nc5  47.Nxe5  dxe5  48.Be3  Nd3  49.d6  e4  50.Bd1  Ra2+  51.Kg3  Ra3  52.d7  1-0 Gschnitzer-Gueci, Graz Chess Open 2023. }
16. Bxb4
{ I didn't play ...axb4 because I missed the best move in this position. }
16... Nb8 { Defending d6 and intending to redeploy the knight via a6. } 17. c4
Na6 18. Ba3 Kh8
{ It was a bit weird for me to put the knight on a6, but the idea is to stop c5 and play ...b6 and ...Nc5 in the future. The chances are equal, but I prefer Black because of the vigorous center and the precise plan to attack the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Modern Main Line 7.Nd5 − 9.a4"]
[Black "Modern Main Line 9.a4 Be7 10.Be2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ The starting position of the Sveshnikov Sicilian. } 6. Ndb5
{ White threatens Nd6+, gaining the bishop pair and control of the dark squares. Black is forced to play ...d6, when it will be harder to push the pawn to d5 in the future. }
6... d6
{ 6...h6  was played many times by the legendary GM Ulf Andersson.  Black allows the entry of the knight on d6.  7.Nd6+  Bxd6  8.Qxd6  Qe7  . How could one of the most famous strategists invent this line? The position seems terrible for Black; he gave up the bishop pair and will enter an endgame with the king  on e7. Even if I don't like it, it's perfectly playable.    9.Qxe7+  Kxe7  10.b3  d6  11.Ba3  a6  12.O-O-O  Rd8  13.Bc4  Be6  14.Bd5  Rac8  15.Kb2  b5  16.Bxc6  Rxc6  17.Rd3  Rb8  18.Nd5+  Bxd5  19.exd5  Rcc8  20.Bb4  Ra8  21.Ba5  g5  22.Re1  Nd7  23.h4  g4  24.f4  gxf3  25.gxf3  Rg8  26.f4  Rac8  27.fxe5  Nxe5  28.Bc3  f6  29.Re4  h5  30.Rd2  Rg4  31.Rde2  Rc5  32.Bxe5  dxe5  33.c4  bxc4  34.bxc4  Rxc4  35.Rxc4  Rxc4  0-1 Berg-Andersson, Katrineholm 1999. }
7. Nd5
{ In my opinion, this is the best option for White. The main line with  7.Bg5  looks more natural, and, honestly, it was the only move I knew for White when I became WFM. But after four years of playing only Sveshnikov with Black, I can say that my most vigorous opponents played  mostly Nd5. It probably became more popular since Fabiano Caruana played it four times against Magnus Carlsen during the World Championship Match 2018.  Is White losing a tempo and violating the opening principle 'don't move the same piece twice'? The threat is Nc7+, so Black is forced to take on d5, and after exd5, it is Black's turn to lose a tempo with the knight on c6. }
7... Nxd5
{ Everyone knows that, if possible, White wants to take with a piece on d5. So why is exd5 the most-played move? }
8. exd5
{ We obtained the structure that GM Mauricio Flores Rios calls Najdorf type 1 in his book Chess Structures. But why are we talking about Najdorf if this is a Sveshnikov course? The structure is the same, so let's call it 'Sveshnikov's structure 3'.  White has a majority on the queenside and plans to advance with b4, c4, and then c5. On the other hand, Black has the activity on the kingside and will play ...f5 and create an attack against White's king. Black often frees play by exchanging the dark-squared bishops via g5 or even h4, which will facilitate attacking maneuvers such as ...Rf8-f6-h6. }
8... Nb8
{ Moving back to the initial square, the knight will go to d7 soon, controlling c5. }
9. a4
{ Preparing to transfer the knight to c4 via a3 and preventing Black's plan with ...b5. }
9... Be7 { Preparing to castle. } 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O
{ 11.Bd2  transposes to the 10.Bd2 move order. } 11... Nd7
{ There is no hurry to play ...a6. It's better to wait until White attacks a7 with Be3 or pushes the pawn to a5. }
12. Bd2
{ The best choice in correspondence chess. It was also played in the World Championship match between Caruana and Carlsen in 2018. }
12... a6
{ I prefer this move rather than Carlsen's  12...f5  ,  to play 13...a5 and avoid a5 from White.   12...f5  13.a5  a6  14.Na3  e4  15.Nc4  Ne5  16.Nb6  Rb8  17.f4  exf3  18.Bxf3  g5  19.c4  f4  20.Bc3  Bf5  21.c5  Nxf3+  22.Qxf3  dxc5  23.Rad1  Bd6  24.h3  Qe8  25.Nc4  Qg6  26.Nxd6  Qxd6  27.h4  gxh4  28.Qxf4  Qxf4  29.Rxf4  h5  30.Re1  Bg4  31.Rf6  Rxf6  32.Bxf6  Kf7  33.Bxh4  Re8  34.Rf1+  Kg8  35.Rf6  Re2  36.Rg6+  Kf8  37.d6  Rd2  38.Rg5  ½-½ Caruana-Carlsen, London 2018. }
13. Na3 a5
{ Black does not lose a tempo with the pawn because the knight is forced to go back. This is a typical theme in the a4 lines of the Sveshnikov. }
14. f4 f5 15. Kh1 Nf6 { Attacking d5. } 16. Be3 exf4 17. Rxf4 Ne4
{ Black almost equalized thanks to the strong knight on e4. } *

