10. Nd5 Bg7
{ I suggest  10...Bg7  instead of the main line  10...f5  because it is Carlsen's favorite. Moreover, there's less theory to know. It is called the Novosibirsk Variation. }
11. g3
{ I encountered this recent sideline twice: in a chess.com Titled Tuesday, and against GM Bokros in Budapest. White wants to fianchetto the bishop, trying to control the light squares. }
11... Ne7
{ I think it is better not to play ...f5 immediately to avoid opening the diagonal in favor of the white bishop. }
12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Bg2 d5
{ The engine's top choice! Of course, it was part of my home preparation. I think it is almost impossible to find it on the board. The idea is to open lines for the pieces, particularly the d-file for our rooks and the diagonal for the black queen. }
14. c3
{ My opponent played the only move I didn't know and he won the game thanks to his strength and experience. }
14... dxe4 15. Bxe4 Rb8
{ Once again, Black is not worried about checks. If Bc6+, simply ...Kf8 and Black is slightly better. }
16. Nc2 f5
{ An extremely important move that, unfortunately, I didn't play.   16...O-O?  17.Ne3  f5  18.Bxf5  Bb7  19.O-O  Qf6  20.Qg4  Qc6  21.f3  Qb6  22.Rae1  Rbd8  23.Rf2  Rd6  24.Kg2  Rfd8  25.Be4  Bc8  26.Nf5  Bxf5  27.Qxf5  h6  28.Ree2  R8d7  29.a3  Qd8  30.f4  exf4  31.Qxf4  Rf6  32.Bf5  Re7  33.Rd2  Qa8+  34.Kh3  h5  35.Rd6  Rxd6  36.Qxd6  Re5  37.Qd1  h4  38.Qh5  Qd5  39.Kxh4  Kf8  40.Kh3  Bf6  41.Qh6+  Ke7  42.Qf4  a5  43.Rd2  Qc6  44.Bg4  Qb6  45.Qh6  b4  46.Rd7+  Ke8  47.Qh7  1-0 Bokros-Gueci, Budapest 2022. }
