O-O Bxd5
{ Black gives the bishop pair to dominate the center.   14...O-O  was played by GM Lautier against GM and World Champion Anand in 1997. Generally speaking, I recommend studying all of Anand's games.  15.Nc2  Nxc2  16.Bxc2  fxe4  17.bxa6  Rxa6  18.Bxe4  f5  19.Bd3  Rc6  20.Be2  Rc5  21.Nc3  e4  22.Rc1  d5  23.Na4  Rxc1  24.Qxc1  d4  25.Nc5  Bd5  26.Bc4  Kh8  27.Ne6  Bxe6  28.Bxe6  d3  29.Qc4  Qf6  30.b3  Re8  31.Bd5  Rd8  32.g3  Qe5  33.Bb7  Qe7  34.Bd5  Qe5  35.Bb7  Qe7  36.Bd5  Qd6  37.Bb7  Qb6  38.Qc6  Qd4  39.Qe6  d2  40.Qxf5  Rf8  0-1 Anand-Lautier, Belgrade 1997. }
15. exd5 e4 16. Be2 Be5
{ As I said before, Black has a fantastic dynamic play thanks to the semi-open g-file. Stockfish 16 gives White the tiniest edge, but defending the king on g1 is very hard. }
17. Nc2 { Fighting Black's number 1. } 17... Nxe2+
{ It is preferable to exchange the knight for the bishop on e2 rather than the knight on c2. }
18. Qxe2 axb5 19. Qxb5+ Kf8
{ The king cannot be attacked on f8, but we cannot say the same for White's king on g1. Despite the pawn deficit, Black is doing fine and will focus on attacking the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Dynamic Line 7.Bg5 − 9.Bxf6 Minor Lines"]
[Black "Dynamic Line 10.Nd5 Bg7 11.Qh5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6
{ The starting position of the theoretical discussions. We already went through  7.Nd5  , the other option, and the main line is  7.Bg5  with the two possibilities of @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nd5  or  9.Bxf6  .  The critical square of every Sicilian  is d5, and we can distinguish the structures where Black plays ...e6 or ...e5. Of course, the Sveshnikov is one of the openings where, by pushing the pawn to e5, Black creates a massive hole on d5, and White usually tries to occupy that with a piece. For these reasons,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  is the best option, trying to eliminate the only defender of  the d5-square and starting the fight for the center. }
7. Bg5 { Pinning the knight on f6. } 7... a6
{ It is essential to chase away the annoying b5-knight and take space on the queenside. }
8. Na3 b5 { Threatening a fork with ...b4. } 9. Bxf6
{ White gives the bishop pair to destroy Black's structure. The general consensus is that Black's activity compensates for the structural weaknesses.   We will deeply analyze the main line  9.Nd5  Be7  in the following chapters. }
9... gxf6
{ These lines are more open and sharper than the ones with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nd5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nd5  . Black can attack the semi-open g-file if White castles short. The doubled pawns  on f7 and f6 look terrible, but it is easy to counter in the center  with ...f5. On the other hand, our king is not super safe, and White has a better structure and an outpost on d5.   9...Qxf6?!  was played by the great Sveshnikov himself. It is a loss of time due to  10.Nd5  Qd8  . In this position, Sveshnikov's opponent played  11.c4  , but there's a more potent option for White.  11.Bxb5!  An unexpected sacrifice. After  11...axb5  12.Nxb5  ,  White has two pawns for the bishop and is threatening Nc7+.  These lines are pretty recent because engines worked differently at the time of Sveshnikov. Nowadays, if you are imprecise, you get punished.  12...Qa5+  13.c3  Ra7  and there's no way to save the exchange, so it is better to sacrifice it!  14.Nxa7  Qxa7±  , we usually say that two minor pieces are stronger than a rook, but White also has two extra pawns, a great central knight, and two passed pawns on the queenside. So White should win the game with accurate play. }
10. Nd5 Bg7
{ I suggest  10...Bg7  instead of the main line  10...f5  because it is Carlsen's favorite. Moreover, there's less theory to know. It is called the Novosibirsk Variation. }
11. Qh5
{ One of the engine's top choices, even if it goes against the principle 'not to develop the queen too early'. }
11... Ne7
{ As GM Michele Godena taught me, it is vital to fight 'the opponent's number 1' or, in other words, the opponent's most active piece. }
12. Ne3 d5 { The dream of every Sicilian player! } 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. O-O-O
{ Taking advantage of the pinned knight on d5. } 14... f5
{ When it is possible, Black should always react with ...d5 or ...f5. } 15.
Rxd5 Qf6
{ Black will probably regain a pawn on e4 or f2, cast out the rook from d5 by developing the bishop to e6 or b7, and demonstrate our superiority of activity. According to Stockfish 16, Black is winning. }
