f5
{ As usual, Black is unafraid to sacrifice a pawn to open the diagonal for the 'green bishop' on g7. I've heard about this definition of green bishop from Karsten Müller, one of my favorite chess authors. When a player has the bishop pair, the 'green bishop' must be the one the opponent doesn't have. It means that the pawns on our side must stay on the squares of the other color. }
17. Qxf5 O-O
{ Black prefers to delay the capture on g2 to stop White from castling long. }
18. Qh3
{ 18.Bf3?  e4  and now we can see how green the bishop  is on g7.  19.Qxd5  Bxd5  20.Be2  Bxb2-+  , Black wins material. }
18... Qxg2 19. Qxg2 Bxg2 20. Rg1 Be4
{ The material is equal, both players have three pawn islands, but Black has already castled and got the bishop pair, so Black has a favorable endgame. }
