{ 13.Bd3  f5  would transpose to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/5pbp/p1np1p2/1p1Np3/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Bd3  Ne7  12.Nxe7  Qxe7  13.Qh5  f5  . }
13... Qb7 { Preparing to break the center with ...d5 or ...f5. } 14. Bd3 f5
{ When possible, it is better to sacrifice the f-pawn to push ...d5 rather than the opposite. }
15. Qg5 f6 { The only way to protect the bishop on g7. } 16. Qh5+ Qf7
{ Usually, Black has a rook on the seventh rank in the Sveshnikov, but this time we're happier to have the queen coming to defend. }
17. Qxf7+ Kxf7 18. exf5
{ You can't be materialistic if you want to play the Sveshnikov. Not only is Black not afraid to sacrifice a pawn but is also ready to give another one to set a trap. }
18... e4 { A thematic blow! } 19. Bc2
{ 19.Bxe4?  Re8  , the pin is fatal.  20.f3  d5  21.O-O-O  dxe4-+  , Black wins the bishop and the game. }
19... Bxf5 20. Rd1 { Attacking the backward pawn on d6. } 20... Rad8 21. O-O d5
{ The evaluation is equal: Black has a strong center and the bishop pair, but White can block on the dark squares and has a better pawn structure due to the isolated pawns on h7 and f6. }
