{ These lines are more open and sharper than the ones with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nd5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nd5  . Black can attack the semi-open g-file if White castles short. The doubled pawns  on f7 and f6 look terrible, but it is easy to counter in the center  with ...f5. On the other hand, our king is not super safe, and White has a better structure and an outpost on d5.   9...Qxf6?!  was played by the great Sveshnikov himself. It is a loss of time due to  10.Nd5  Qd8  . In this position, Sveshnikov's opponent played  11.c4  , but there's a more potent option for White.  11.Bxb5!  An unexpected sacrifice. After  11...axb5  12.Nxb5  ,  White has two pawns for the bishop and is threatening Nc7+.  These lines are pretty recent because engines worked differently at the time of Sveshnikov. Nowadays, if you are imprecise, you get punished.  12...Qa5+  13.c3  Ra7  and there's no way to save the exchange, so it is better to sacrifice it!  14.Nxa7  Qxa7±  , we usually say that two minor pieces are stronger than a rook, but White also has two extra pawns, a great central knight, and two passed pawns on the queenside. So White should win the game with accurate play. }
10. Nd5 Bg7
{ I suggest  10...Bg7  instead of the main line  10...f5  because it is Carlsen's favorite. Moreover, there's less theory to know. It is called the Novosibirsk Variation. }
11. c3
{ A more strategic approach compared to the other alternatives. Even if this is the most-played continuation, I don't think it is the most critical line. }
11... f5
{ Black starts contesting the light squares and opens the game for the two bishops. This is the essence of the Sveshnikov: grab space, files, and diagonals, and question the opponent's domination over d5 and f5. As I already pointed out, every time White pushes the c-pawns, Black must react with ...f5. This 'rule' applies only to this specific structure. }
12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Nc2
{ The most logical, White played c3 to bring the knight into the game. } 13...
O-O 14. Nce3 Be6
{ Since White will attack h7 with Bd3, Black wants to push ...f5; additionally, the bishop stands better on e6 rather than g6 due to its vulnerability to the push of the white h-pawn. }
15. g3
{ Not the best way to develop the bishop, but we can't say it is wrong. } 15...
f5 16. Bg2 Ra7
{ 16...Rb8  has more games, but I like to put the rook  on a7 to defend the seventh rank. }
17. O-O
{ After other moves, such as  17.Qh5  or  17.f4  , we have a plethora of choices. For example,  17.Qh5  can be met quietly by  17...Kh8  ,  which prepares to expel the queen with ...Bf7 since Qxf5 would run into ...Bxd5, or more aggressively by  @@StartFEN@@3q1rk1/r5bp/p1npb3/1p1Npp1Q/8/2P1N1P1/PP3PBP/R3K2R b KQ - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...b4  , as the pawn is taboo.  Taking it would allow us too much control in the center and that spells trouble for White.  Additionally, @@StartFEN@@3q1rk1/r5bp/p1npb3/1p1Npp1Q/8/2P1N1P1/PP3PBP/R3K2R b KQ - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Ne7  is also an option, which clearly indicates that we're spoilt for choice.   Against  17.f4  , we have a similar story. You can pick out of the hat any move you like, such as  17...Kh8  @@StartBracket@@this mysterious move prepares  ...Bxd5  in some variations, when our king won't have to face a check@@EndBracket@@,  17...e4  ,  17...Ne7  ,  17...a5  , and have no worries whatsoever. Black is fine. }
17... f4 { Black starts to seize the initiative. } 18. gxf4 exf4 19. Nxf4 Rxf4
20. Bxc6 Be5 { Now you can see why Black put the rook on a7. } 21. Ng2
{ Only move. } 21... Qf6
{ Black stops Kh1 due to ...Rxf2. White has to find Bd5 not to be worse. It is a long, hard line, but I will play it with Black. }
22. Nxf4 Qxf4 23. Qh5
{ Attention not to play ...Rg7+. Who gives a check without a purpose will regret it sooner or later. It sounds better in Italian with the rhyme, but the concept is the same. }
23... Kh8 24. f3 Bf7
{ This is the only winning move for Black. It is essential to deflect the white queen from the defense on h2.  25.Qh3  Rc7  26.Be4  Be6  27.Qh5  Rg7+  28.Kh1  Bg4-+  . }
*

