{ The rook on a8 can be attacked after ...fxe4 Bxe4, so Black improves its position. }
16. exf5 e4 { Opening the long diagonal. } 17. Rae1
{ White uses the pin to deal with ...exd3 and ...Bxb2. } 17... Bb7
{ It is necessary to defend the pawn. I've been in this position many times, and it is my favorite line of the Sveshnikov. In this position, Black has to be ready to invest material, but it is proof that the absolute value of the pieces is nothing in comparison to the relative one! Maybe I like it also because I have excellent scores: I didn't lose a single game. }
18. Qg4 { Pinning the bishop and adding an attacker to the e4-pawn. } 18...
Rfe8 { Black must defend the central pawn. } 19. cxb5
{ In this position, the main move is  19...d5  but the best one is  19...Kh8! }
19... Kh8
{ Black frees the dark-squared bishop and prepares the attack with ...Rg8. }
20. bxa6 Ba8
{ White has three extra pawns. This is the game I was talking about before. Imagine the faces of my teammates while watching my game! Luckily for them, I studied the theory and plans of the Sveshnikov very well. }
21. Nb5 { The best option for White, improving the position of the knight. }
21... d5 22. a4 Rb6 { A good move played in an ICCF email game. } 23. a5 Rh6
{ White must stop ...Be5, so the only move is Qf4.   23...Rxa6?  Pay attention not to be greedy, or you will be punished. After  24.Nc7  Qxc7  25.Bxa6+-  , White has more material and wins. }
24. Qf4 Rh4 25. Qd6
{ If White could exchange queens, White would be better. Fortunately, Black has ...Be5, which makes everything more complicated. }
25... Be5 26. Qxe7 Bxh2+ 27. Kh1 Rxe7
{ White still has two extra pawns, but Black has more than enough compensation. }
28. Be2
{ Black can repeat the position with  28...Bf4+  29.Kg1  Bh2+  and make a draw. }
28... d4 29. Nxd4 Be5+ 30. Kg1 Bxd4
{ Black can play this position and fight for a slight advantage if we want more than a draw. }
