7. Bg5 { Pinning the knight on f6. } 7... a6
{ It is essential to chase away the annoying knight on b5 and take space on the queenside. }
8. Na3
{ 8.Bxf6  gxf6  9.Na3  b5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bxf6  move order. }
8... b5
{ Black is threatening a fork with ...b4. Apart from  9.Bxf6  , White has only two options: the main line  9.Nd5  and the awkward  9.Nab1  . }
9. Bxf6
{ White gives the bishop pair to destroy Black's structure. The general consensus is that Black's activity compensates for the structural weaknesses. }
9... gxf6
{ These lines are more open and sharper than the ones with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nd5  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nd5  .  Black can attack the semi-open g-file if White castles short. The doubled pawns on f7 and f6 look terrible, but it is easy to counter in the center with ...f5. On the other hand, our king is not super safe, and White has a better structure and an outpost on d5. }
10. Nd5 Bg7
{ We have the Novosibirsk Variation on the board, which was discussed in the relevant chapter. }
