12. Bd3 f5
{ A thematic break in the center! One way or another, Black will conquer the e4-square. }
13. Bxe7 Kxe7
{ Stockfish 16's favorite option. I didn't suggest it as the main line because I understand it is not human, but it deserves a mention. If you feel brave, then go for it! }
14. exf5
{ After  14.exd5  Qxd5  ,  White has to take care of the g2-pawn, while our moves come naturally: ...Rg8, ...Be6, ...Nd4, etc, depending on the circumstances. Black has quite a significant advantage already. }
14... e4 15. Be2 d4 { Black gains more and more space. } 16. Qd2
{ Defending the pawn with  16.Bg4  runs into another problem:  16...Qa5+  . Now, if White exchanges queens,  our king will be perfectly installed on f6 in the endgame, while after  17.Kf1  h5  18.Bh3  Bb7  ,  the king proves to be an asset rather than a weakness. The f6-square is again a nice-looking throne for the monarch in some variations, but the ...Ne5 and ...f6 combo can be considered too. The engines evaluate this position as lost for White. }
16... Bxf5
{ The king cannot be attacked on e7, and Black has a better position.   Just to reassure the readers that we shouldn't worry about our very healthy king, after  17.Qg5+  Ke6  18.Qf4  Qd6  19.Qh6+  Ke7  , it is not so easy for White to avoid the exchange of queens, which would put an end to any potential fears regarding the king's safety.   If White insists on keeping the queens on the board with  18.Qh5  for example, after  18...Rg8  19.O-O  , the engine is not even interested anymore to reach an endgame and suggests  19...Qf6  ,  with a -4 evaluation! }
