7. Bg5 { Pinning the knight on f6. } 7... a6
{ It is essential to chase away the annoying knight on b5 and take space on the queenside. }
8. Na3
{ 8.Bxf6  gxf6  9.Na3  b5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bxf6  move order. }
8... b5
{ Black is threatening a fork with ...b4. Apart from  9.Bxf6  , White has only two options: the main line  9.Nd5  and the awkward  9.Nab1  . }
9. Nd5
{ We will master the most known theoretical lines of the Sveshnikov Sicilian.  9.Nd5  is considered to be a positional move, especially if compared with  9.Bxf6  .  Black will not have the doubled pawns because we will capture on f6 with the bishop. }
9... Be7
{ Unpinning the knight and attacking the pawn on e4. In this position, the only good move for White is  10.Bxf6  , while  10.Nxe7  is playable and  10.Nxf6+  is dubious. }
10. Bxf6 { The only reasonable option for White. } 10... Bxf6 11. Be2
{ White doesn't define the pawn structure but delays the maneuver with Nc2-e3. }
11... O-O 12. c3 { White prepares Nc2. } 12... Bg5
{ The best square for the dark-squared bishop in the Sveshnikov. Since White will put a knight in e3 to dominate the d5-square, Black will be ready to face it with ...Bxe3. }
13. O-O Ne7 { Fighting the opponent's 'number one': the best-placed piece. }
14. Nxe7+ Qxe7
{ This exchange usually favors Black, who has already solved the issue with d5. }
15. Nc2 Bb7 { Black attacks the center and is ready to push ...d5. } 16. Bf3 d5
{ This is not the only good move, but I think it is coherent with Black's plan to conquer the central squares and open the position for the bishop pair. }
17. exd5 e4
{ Black must be cautious about playing ...e4; sometimes, it can be wrong because it leaves White the d4-square. In this case, even if the white knight goes to d4, it doesn't create any threat. }
18. Re1 { White defends the bishop by pinning the e4-pawn. } 18... f5
{ Black has the initiative. } *

