{ This is the main line in the Sveshnikov. Both  11.c3  and  11.c4  intend to bring  the a3-knight into the game via c2, but there are essential differences between the two moves. The pawn on c3 controls d4, which can be an outpost for the black knight. And leaves the door open to realize a breakthrough with a4, which is not good with the pawn on c4.  We can say that the first option is more strategic, which is why it was the only one played in the past. Our predecessors strictly followed the general principles and rules, while today, we are used to thinking critically without having prejudices. }
11... O-O 12. Bd3
{ I'm usually happy when my opponents put the bishop on d3 because the white pawn blocks it, but the idea is to transfer it to b3 via c2. This plan is a bit too slow to be the best one.   12.Be2  Bg5  transposes to the 11.Be2 variation. }
12... Bg5
{ After O-O, Black usually improves the bishop's position to be ready against the idea with Nc2-e3. }
13. Bc2 g6 { Black can follow the same setup. } 14. Bb3 Be6 15. O-O Na5
{ Now it is evident that White is not going anywhere with the bishop. } 16. Nc2
{ There are many possible moves. I suggest continuing with ...Ra7 and ...Qb8. }
16... Ra7 { Black's pieces are harmonious, and we have a very slight edge. } *

