10. Bxf6 { The only reasonable option for White. } 10... Bxf6 11. c3
{ This is the main line in the Sveshnikov. Both  11.c3  and  11.c4  intend to bring  the a3-knight into the game via c2, but there are essential differences between the two moves. The pawn on c3 controls d4, which can be an outpost for the black knight. And leaves the door open to realize a breakthrough with a4, which is not good with the pawn on c4.  We can say that the first option is more strategic, which is why it was the only one played in the past. Our predecessors strictly followed the general principles and rules, while today, we are used to thinking critically without having prejudices. }
11... O-O 12. Nc2
{ Black has many common choices; my favorite is  12...Rb8  to prevent White's plan  with a4. If  12...Bg5  , I suggest to my students to play  13.a4  for White, so I don't go for the most common move.   12.Be2  Bg5  transposes to the 11.Be2 variation. }
12... Rb8 13. Be2
{ These slow moves that don't directly act on the kingside @@StartBracket@@g3-h4@@EndBracket@@ or the queenside @@StartBracket@@a4@@EndBracket@@ are solid but not dangerous. }
13... Bg5 { White does not have so many options here. } 14. O-O
{ There are several options for Black. In 2019 I played  14...Kh8  inspired by Carlsen, but I got annoyed by  15.Ncb4  , so I concluded that it is preferable to avoid it by playing @@StartFEN@@1rbq1rk1/5ppp/p1np4/1p1Np1b1/4P3/2P5/PPN1BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 6 14@@EndFEN@@  14...a5  .   14.Qd3  a5  15.O-O  Ne7  transposes to 14.O-O. }
14... a5
{ 14...Kh8  was inspired by Giri-Carlsen ½-½ 2019.  15.Ncb4  Nxb4  16.Nxb4  Qb6  17.a4  bxa4  18.Qxa4  Bb7  19.Nxa6  Bxa6  20.Qxa6  Qxb2  21.Ra2  Qxc3  22.Qxd6  Rfd8  23.Qa3  Qd4  24.Qa7  f6  25.Qxd4  Rxd4  26.Bf3  g6  27.g3  Rb7  28.Kg2  Kg7  29.h4  Bh6  30.Rfa1  Rdb4  ½-½ Tomashevskaya-Gueci, Skopje 2019. }
15. Bg4
{ A minor move with a traditional idea: exchange the light-squared bishops to have exclusive possession of d5 and f5. }
15... Be6
{ Black is not afraid of the doubled pawns if White takes on e6 and is even happy about the structural change because it drastically solves the problem with the light squares and opens the file for the rook. }
16. Bxe6 fxe6 { Black controls both f5 and d5. } 17. Nde3 Qd7
{ Black is ready to relocate the knight to f7 to defend the weakness on d6. White's plan is not clear now that White does not have the center anymore. The situation is balanced. }
*

