{ The starting position of the theoretical discussions. We already went through  7.Nd5  and  7.Bg5  with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bxf6  , so we have to discuss @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nd5  , which can be divided into @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/5ppp/p1np1b2/1p1Np3/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.c3  and  11.c4  .   The critical square of every Sicilian is d5, and we can distinguish the structures where Black plays ...e6 or ...e5. Of course, the Sveshnikov is one of the openings where, by pushing the pawn to e5, Black creates a massive hole on d5, and White usually tries to occupy that with a piece. For these reasons,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  is the best option, trying to eliminate the only defender of  the d5-square and starting the fight for the center. }
7. Bg5 { Pinning the knight on f6. } 7... a6
{ It is essential to chase away the annoying knight on b5 and take space on the queenside. }
8. Na3
{ 8.Bxf6  gxf6  9.Na3  b5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bxf6  move order. }
8... b5
{ Black is threatening a fork with ...b4. Apart from  9.Bxf6  , White has only two options: the main line  9.Nd5  and the awkward  9.Nab1  . }
9. Nd5
{ We will master the most known theoretical lines of the Sveshnikov Sicilian.  9.Nd5  is considered to be a positional move, especially if compared with  9.Bxf6  .  Black will not have the doubled pawns because we will capture on f6 with the bishop. }
9... Be7
{ Unpinning the knight and attacking the pawn on e4. In this position, the only good move for White is  10.Bxf6  , while  10.Nxe7  is playable and  10.Nxf6+  is dubious. }
10. Bxf6 { The only reasonable option for White. } 10... Bxf6 11. c3
{ This is the main line in the Sveshnikov. Both  11.c3  and  11.c4  intend to bring  the a3-knight into the game via c2, but there are essential differences between the two moves. The pawn on c3 controls d4, which can be an outpost for the black knight. And leaves the door open to realize a breakthrough with a4, which is not good with the pawn on c4.  We can say that the first option is more strategic, which is why it was the only one played in the past. Our predecessors strictly followed the general principles and rules, while today, we are used to thinking critically without having prejudices. }
11... O-O 12. Nc2
{ Black has many common choices; my favorite is  12...Rb8  to prevent White's plan  with a4. If  12...Bg5  , I suggest to my students to play  13.a4  for White, so I don't go for the most common move.   12.Be2  Bg5  transposes to the 11.Be2 variation. }
12... Rb8 13. a4
{ This is playable even though it doesn't create any problems for Black. }
13... bxa4 { The point of ...Rb8 is to put pressure on b2. } 14. Ncb4
{ The most sound. White avoids ...Rxb2 and tries to exchange minor pieces. }
14... Nxb4 15. cxb4 Bb7
{ In this variation, the bishop goes to b7 to put pressure on e4 and to protect a6. }
16. Rxa4
{ White is threatening Bxa6; how to react? There are different right moves, but adding a defender with ...Qc8 is the most logical. }
16... Qc8
{ Played by Carlsen against Vachier-Lagrave in 2015. Black hopes to capture d5 and exploit the c1-square with the queen. }
17. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ At this point of the course, you already know there's nothing to be afraid of with the two doubled f-pawns. }
18. Bd3 Rd8
{ ...d5 is coming next.   18...Bc6  19.Rxa6  Rxb4  20.O-O  Rd4  21.Qf3  Bxe4  22.Bxe4  Qxa6  23.Qg4+  Kh8  24.Qf5  Rxe4  25.Qxf6+  Kg8  26.Qg5+  Kh8  27.Qf6+  Kg8  28.Qg5+  Kh8  ½-½ MVL-Carlsen, London 2015. }
19. O-O d5 20. exd5 Rxd5 { Black has a great initiative on the kingside. } *

