{ Black has many common choices; my favorite is  12...Rb8  to prevent White's plan  with a4. If  12...Bg5  , I suggest to my students to play  13.a4  for White, so I don't go for the most common move.   12.Be2  Bg5  transposes to the 11.Be2 variation. }
12... Rb8 13. g3
{ The fianchetto variation is common among beginners because White develops the pieces without knowing too much theory. It is more common with @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/5ppp/p1np1b2/1p1Np3/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.c4  . }
13... Bg5
{ Black's response against almost all the opponent's options at move 13 besides h4. }
14. Bg2 a5 15. O-O
{ 15.h4  Bh6  would transpose to @@StartFEN@@1rbq1rk1/5ppp/p1np4/1p1Np1b1/4P3/2P3P1/PPN2P1P/R2QKB1R w KQ - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14.h4  Bh6  15.Bg2  . }
15... Ne7 { Black's goal is to trade the knights. } 16. Nce3
{ The majority of players took on e3 in this position. I have a preference for  16...Nxd5  . }
16... Nxd5 { GM Michalik's idea. } 17. Nxd5 Be6 18. h4 Bh6 19. Qd3 Kh8 20. Rfd1
g6
{ The situation is balanced: White is trying to attack d6 and has the d5-square, while Black can play on both flanks and has the bishop pair.   21.Qe2  Qc8  22.Ne3  Qc5  23.Rd3  b4  24.Nd5  f5  25.Rad1  Bd7  26.b3  Rf7  27.c4  Rbf8  28.Rf1  fxe4  29.Bxe4  Bg4  30.Qe1  Bh3  31.Bg2  Bf5  32.Rd1  Bc2  33.Rd2  Bxd2  34.Qxd2  Bf5  35.Ne3  Bd7  36.Bd5  Rf6  37.Kg2  Qd4  38.Qe2  e4  39.Nd1  Bf5  40.Re1  h5  41.Ne3  Bg4  42.Nxg4  hxg4  43.Rf1  Qd3  44.Qxe4  Qd2  45.Qe1  Qxe1  46.Rxe1  Rxf2+  47.Kg1  Rxa2  48.Re3  Rff2  49.Re8+  Kg7  50.Re7+  Kf8  51.Re6  Rfb2  52.Rf6+  Kg7  53.Rxd6  Ra1#  0-1 Havelka-Michalik, Czech Republic 2022. }
