{ 8.Bxf6  gxf6  9.Na3  b5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bxf6  move order. }
8... b5
{ Black is threatening a fork with ...b4. Apart from  9.Bxf6  , White has only two options: the main line  9.Nd5  and the awkward  9.Nab1  . }
9. Nd5
{ We will master the most known theoretical lines of the Sveshnikov Sicilian.  9.Nd5  is considered to be a positional move, especially if compared with  9.Bxf6  .  Black will not have the doubled pawns because we will capture on f6 with the bishop. }
9... Be7
{ Unpinning the knight and attacking the pawn on e4. In this position, the only good move for White is  10.Bxf6  , while  10.Nxe7  is playable and  10.Nxf6+  is dubious. }
10. Bxf6 { The only reasonable option for White. } 10... Bxf6 11. c3
{ This is the main line in the Sveshnikov. Both  11.c3  and  11.c4  intend to bring  the a3-knight into the game via c2, but there are essential differences between the two moves. The pawn on c3 controls d4, which can be an outpost for the black knight. And leaves the door open to realize a breakthrough with a4, which is not good with the pawn on c4.  We can say that the first option is more strategic, which is why it was the only one played in the past. Our predecessors strictly followed the general principles and rules, while today, we are used to thinking critically without having prejudices. }
11... O-O 12. Nc2
{ Black has many common choices; my favorite is  12...Rb8  to prevent White's plan  with a4. If  12...Bg5  , I suggest to my students to play  13.a4  for White, so I don't go for the most common move.   12.Be2  Bg5  transposes to the 11.Be2 variation. }
12... Rb8 13. Qf3
{ Played by GM Conquest − it is strange to me, but it is in the engine's top five, so it deserves mention. The idea is to push h4 and g4 as soon as possible against ...Bg5 or to ruin the structure with Nxf6+ if Black doesn't go away with the bishop. }
13... Bg5 14. h4 Bh6 15. g4 Bf4
{ One way to save the bishop together with ...f6. } 16. Nxf4
{ 16.a3  a5  transposes to the 13.a3 variation. } 16... exf4 17. Qxf4 b4
{ Thanks to the exposed white king, Black has more than compensation for the pawn. }
*

