{ I also played  13...g6  and concluded that it is safer not to change the pawn structure. White wants to keep the dominance of d5 by playing Nce3, Qf3, and sometimes Bd3-c2-b3.   Once again, after  13...Bxh4??  14.Qh5  Bxf2+  15.Kxf2  h6-+  , White wins the bishop and the game. }
14. Nce3 Be6 15. Qf3 { 15.Bd3  Qd7  would transpose to 14.Bd3. } 15... Qd7
{ ...Bd8, ...Kh8, and ...Ne7 are coming next. } 16. Rd1 Bd8 17. Be2
{ The bishop on e2 doesn't interfere with the activity of the rook against d6. }
17... Ne7 18. h5 h6
{ Pay attention not to let White play h6. The two ways to stop it are ...h6 or ...Bg5 when possible. }
19. O-O Qc8
{ Going away with the queen from the same file as the opponent's rook. Black can improve it by putting it on c5. }
20. Nxe7+ Bxe7 21. Nf5 { Attacking both the bishop and the pawn. } 21... Qc7
22. Qg3 Bg5 { Black avoids getting mated. } 23. Nxd6 Bf4
{ Black sacrifices the weak pawn. } 24. Qf3 g6
{ White has only one unclear move, not to be worse. } 25. c4
{ White must save the knight. } 25... Rb6 26. Qa3 b4 27. Qa5
{ Thanks to a pin, White doesn't lose material. } 27... Qe7
{ Black hunts the big fish. } 28. Qxb6 Qh4 29. g3 Bxg3 30. fxg3 Qxg3+ 31. Kh1
Qh3+ { It all ends with a perpetual check. } *

