12. Nc2 { The knight retreat is almost forced. } 12... O-O
{ I played both  12...O-O  and  12...a5  ,  and I wondered which one was more precise every time. It is often just a transposition, but ...O-O is more flexible. A critical line is  12...a5  13.Qf3  .   Here's the difference with 12...O-O. After  12...a5  ,  13.Qf3  is annoying because  it threatens Nxf6+ to force Black to leave with the bishop.  13...Bg5  14.h4  Bh6  15.g4  and  the issue with g5 cannot be solved by ...f6 because the king on e8 would be in danger, while 12...O-O consents to play ...f6 in a similar line.  15...f6?  16.g5  and Qh5+ is coming next. Following  16...fxg5  17.Qh5+  Kf8+-  , White is winning due to the vulnerable black king. }
13. Be2 { A positional setup. } 13... a5
{ Black wants to play ...a5 only after avoiding 13.Qf3. } 14. O-O Bg5 15. Qd3
{ White decides not to play Bg4 anymore to connect the rooks. } 15... Be6 16.
Rad1 g6
{ When I started playing the Sveshnikov, I thought that ...g6 helped me achieve the ...f5 push; then, I understood that ...f5 is a double-edged move because it opens the diagonals for the white bishop. Indeed, Black has not decided yet whether to push the pawn or not and wants to give a safe place to the king. }
17. b3 Kg7
{ The main line continues with  17...Ra7  , but  17...Kg7  is more  coherent with ...g6. Now Black can decide what to do depending on White's plans. }
18. Kh1
{ If White doesn't take a decision, this is the right moment to eliminate the strong central knight. Black would like to move the queen, but no good squares exist. After ...Bxd5, we can bring the queen to c5 via b6. }
18... Bxd5 19. exd5
{ This is a victory for Black, who can attack the kingside with the center closed. }
19... Nb8 { White must sacrifice a pawn to avoid a worse position. } 20. c5
{ Otherwise, Black would have a splendid knight on c5. } 20... dxc5 21. d6 a4
{ White has compensation for the pawn but must play accurately. } *

