13... a5 { Black defends the pawn. } 14. g3
{ By far the most played − White plays directly on the kingside. } 14... Be6
15. Bg2 { A solid move that doesn't create theoretical difficulties. } 15... g6
{ Black needs an alternative place for the bishop and frees the g7-square. Some of you may be worried about giving a 'contact point' on h5, but White's attack is harmless. }
16. Qd3 Ra7
{ A multifunctional move: it defends the seventh rank and sometimes helps keep the backward pawn alive with ...Rd7. }
17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Qxd6
{ It looks scary because it captures a pawn and attacks c6, but it is a dubious choice. }
18... Rc8 19. Qd3 Rd7 20. Qf3
{ Black can also trade queens and immediately gain back material with  20...Bxc4  , but if you are a Sveshniov player, you don't mind being a pawn down for a couple of moves. }
20... Qe7 21. b3 Rcd8 { Black rules on the d-file. } 22. Ne3
{ White tries to make ...Rd3 less powerful.  22.O-O?  loses material due to  22...Rd3  23.Qe2  Rd2-+  , when Black wins the knight and the game. }
22... Rd2 { Black enters on the second rank! } 23. Nd5
{ A nice interference − with a small calculation, Black has nothing to be afraid of. }
23... Bxd5 24. exd5 Nd4 { Saving both pieces. } 25. Qg4 f5 26. Qg5 Qxg5 27.
hxg5 Re2+ { Black denies White's possibility to castle. } 28. Kf1 Rd2
{ Black has tremendous activity. } *

