{ The starting position of the theoretical discussions. We already went through  7.Nd5  and  7.Bg5  with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bxf6  , so we have to discuss @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nd5  , which can be divided into @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/5ppp/p1np1b2/1p1Np3/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.c3  and  11.c4  .   The critical square of every Sicilian is d5, and we can distinguish the structures where Black plays ...e6 or ...e5. Of course, the Sveshnikov is one of the openings where, by pushing the pawn to e5, Black creates a massive hole on d5, and White usually tries to occupy that with a piece. For these reasons,  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  is the best option, trying to eliminate the only defender of  the d5-square and starting the fight for the center. }
7. Bg5 { Pinning the knight on f6. } 7... a6
{ It is essential to chase away the annoying knight on b5 and take space on the queenside. }
8. Na3
{ 8.Bxf6  gxf6  9.Na3  b5  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bxf6  move order. }
8... b5
{ Black is threatening a fork with ...b4. Apart from  9.Bxf6  , White has only two options: the main line  9.Nd5  and the awkward  9.Nab1  . }
9. Nd5
{ We will master the most known theoretical lines of the Sveshnikov Sicilian.  9.Nd5  is considered to be a positional move, especially if compared with  9.Bxf6  .  Black will not have the doubled pawns because we will capture on f6 with the bishop. }
9... Be7
{ Unpinning the knight and attacking the pawn on e4. In this position, the only good move for White is  10.Bxf6  , while  10.Nxe7  is playable and  10.Nxf6+  is dubious. }
10. Bxf6 { The only reasonable option for White. } 10... Bxf6 11. c4
{ The second most played. Both  11.c3  and  11.c4  intend to bring  the a3-knight into the game via c2, but there are essential differences between the two moves. The pawn on c3 controls d4, which can be an outpost for the black knight. And leaves the door open to achieve a breakthrough with a4, which is not good with the pawn on c4.  The first option is more strategic, which is why it was the only one played in the past. Our predecessors strictly followed the general principles and rules, while today, we are used to thinking critically without having prejudices. Another difference is that c4 attacks b5 and forces Black to play ...b4. }
11... b4
{ Black rarely wants to capture on c4 − remember that White is trying to dominate the light squares. }
12. Nc2 { The knight retreat is almost forced. } 12... O-O
{ I played both  12...O-O  and  12...a5  ,  and I wondered which one was more precise every time. It is often just a transposition, but ...O-O is more flexible. A critical line is  12...a5  13.Qf3  .   Here's the difference with 12...O-O. After  12...a5  ,  13.Qf3  is annoying because  it threatens Nxf6+ to force Black to leave with the bishop.  13...Bg5  14.h4  Bh6  15.g4  and  the issue with g5 cannot be solved by ...f6 because the king on e8 would be in danger, while 12...O-O consents to play ...f6 in a similar line.  15...f6?  16.g5  and Qh5+ is coming next. Following  16...fxg5  17.Qh5+  Kf8+-  , White is winning due to the vulnerable black king. }
13. h4
{ The only way to prevent ...Bg5. As we went through in the previous chapters, although the structure was slightly different, White wants to continue with g3 and Bh3. Many GMs, such as Caruana, So, and Nakamura, used this weapon. }
13... a5 { Black defends the pawn. } 14. g3
{ By far the most played − White plays directly on the kingside. } 14... Be6
15. Bh3 a4
{ If White doesn't stop it, Black wants to go for ...a4 and ...b3. Black doesn't like to exchange the bishops but waits for Bxe6 to capture with the pawn and solve the issues with the light squares. }
16. Kf1 { White goes for an artificial castle. } 16... b3 17. Nce3 Nd4 18. Kg2
{ White prefers to maintain the tension between a2 and b3. } 18... Rb8
{ Black puts pressure on the b-file. } 19. a3
{ Closing the queenside is not a wise decision because it leaves Black with all the play on the kingside. }
19... g6 20. Nxf6+ Qxf6 21. h5 { White must find some counterplay. } 21... Rb7
{ Black is slightly better and can put pressure on the weakness on c4. } *

