{ Black rarely wants to capture on c4 − remember that White is trying to dominate the light squares. }
12. Nc2 { The knight retreat is almost forced. } 12... O-O
{ I played both  12...O-O  and  12...a5  ,  and I wondered which one was more precise every time. It is often just a transposition, but ...O-O is more flexible. A critical line is  12...a5  13.Qf3  .   Here's the difference with 12...O-O. After  12...a5  ,  13.Qf3  is annoying because  it threatens Nxf6+ to force Black to leave with the bishop.  13...Bg5  14.h4  Bh6  15.g4  and  the issue with g5 cannot be solved by ...f6 because the king on e8 would be in danger, while 12...O-O consents to play ...f6 in a similar line.  15...f6?  16.g5  and Qh5+ is coming next. Following  16...fxg5  17.Qh5+  Kf8+-  , White is winning due to the vulnerable black king. }
13. Qf3
{ As mentioned, Qf3 is crucial against @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/5ppp/p1np1b2/3Np3/1pP1P3/8/PPN2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12...a5  , but there's nothing to be afraid of with this move order. }
13... Bg5 14. h4 Bh6 15. g4
{ White threatens to trap the bishop. If you wonder what the difference is with the pawn on c3 rather than c4, go to the previous chapter. }
15... f6
{ With the castle included, White cannot go for g5 because, after ...fxg5, the rook attacks the queen. }
16. Be2 Be6 { Played by GM Gelfand against GM Lagarde in 2021. } 17. Ndxb4
{ Slightly better than  17.Ncxb4  because it doesn't allow ...Nd4. } 17... Nxb4
18. Nxb4 Qb6
{ White gives Black what we want: the initiative and the possibility to remove the opponent's knight from the center. }
19. a3 a5 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. cxd5 Qxb2 { Black wins back the pawn. } 22. O-O Rab8
{ With the opposite-colored bishops, the player with more activity has more chances. The situation is balanced, but White's king is more vulnerable due to the pawns on the fourth rank. }
*

