1. Bh4
{ White leaves Black the initiative and has some issues with the dark squares. }
1... Qa5 { Pinning the knight and threatening both ...Rxb2 and ...Nxe4. } 2.
Bxf6
{ After  2.Qf3  ,  it seems that White stops both threats, but that isn't the case!  2...Nxe4!  3.Qxe4  Rxb2!  Black sacrifices the knight and the rook to destroy the enemy's defense.  4.Rxb2  Qxc3+  5.Kd1  Qxb2-+  and Black takes back the material with interest. }
2... Rxb2
{ An intermediate move that disrupts White's chance of staying in the game. }
3. Kd2
{ At least it protects c3.   3.Rxb2  Qxc3+  4.Qd2  Qxb2-+  and given ...gxf6 and ...Bb4, White can resign:  5.Bh4  Bb4  . }
3... Bb4
{ The most elegant choice, bringing another piece to the party! Now it's impossible to save both the knight on c3 and the bishop on f6. }
4. Rxb2 Bxc3+ 5. Ke2 Qa4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Tactics"]
[Black "Eliminating the e4-pawn #1 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pp2bppp/2np1n2/4p3/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nc4
{ Generally speaking, White is happy to redirect the knight to d5 via c4-e3 but must be careful because tactics are everywhere. }
1... Nxe4 2. Nxe4 d5
{ Black eliminates the central pawn and gives a fork to win back one knight. }
3. Ng3
{ After  3.Nxe5  Nxe5  4.Ng3  O-O⩱  ,  Black has an isolated pawn on d5, but the files are open for the pieces, and White still has to castle so is slightly worse. }
3... dxc4 4. Qxd8+ Bxd8 5. Bxc4 Nb4 6. Bb3 Be6
{ Black forces White's king to move and lose the opportunity to castle. You may wonder why I consider it a tactic since, in the end, the material is equal; the answer is that ...Nxe4 and ...d5 created a fork, and every time that Black manages to capture the e4-pawn, it can be considered a small victory. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Tactics"]
[Black "Eliminating the e4-pawn #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/pp2bppp/2np1n2/4p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP1QPPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1... Nxe4
{ Another blow against the e4-pawn. Black takes advantage of the unprotected bishop on g5. }
2. Bxe7
{ Even though this is not White's best option, I'm putting it as the main line because it is a bit harder to calculate.   2.Qxe4  Bxg5  is simply gaining a pawn.   The engine's favorite is  2.Nxe4  , but  2...Bxg5  3.Qg4  Bh6⩱  keeps the material advantage. }
2... Nxc3
{ Calculation is one of the most challenging things in chess. A tip I can give you: when you understand that your visualization doesn't work well and you are not sure about material count anymore, it is better to repeat in your head the pieces that every player captures during the analysis. For example, I'd go through this line by thinking: ...Nxe4 wins a pawn, Bxe7 White captures a bishop, and ...Nxc3 Black takes a knight. }
3. Bxd8 { White captures the queen.   3.bxc3  Qxe7-+ } 3... Nxe2
{ Black gains back the queen. } 4. Bc7 Ned4
{ And at the end of the line, Black has an extra pawn. } 5. Bxd6 O-O-O 6. Bc5
Nf5
{ White equalized the material balance but is slightly worse due to a lack in development. }
*

