{ White has played h3; how should Black react to maintain the material balance? }
1... e4
{ It's the only winning move. White has significant pressure on the g-file, whereas Black has two bishops. At first sight, it seems that Black is losing, but thanks to the dark-squared bishop, we have decisive pressure on b2. It is similar to the previous diagram but requires more calculation. }
2. Rb1
{ After  2.hxg4  Bxb2  ,  Black is not interested in capturing the white bishop. Instead, Black prefers to create problems for the rook and knight.  3.Rb1  Bxa3  4.Be2  f4-+  ,  Black has two extra pawns and, as we learned, there's a considerable activity difference between the opposite-colored bishops, which favors the dark-squared one.   2.Be2  Bxb2  ,  Black's certain response if White doesn't defend b2.  3.Rb1  Bc3+  4.Kd1  @@StartBracket@@  4.Kf1  Bxh3+-+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/5p1p/p2p4/1p1P1p2/4p1b1/N1b4P/P1P1BP2/1R1K2R1 b kq - 3 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bxe2+  5.Kxe2  Ke7-+  and the advantage is huge thanks to the misplaced knight. }
2... exd3 3. hxg4 Rc8
{ The most accurate way to exploit the advantage: ...dxc2 is coming next, and if White captures d3, it directly falls into another tactic. }
4. cxd3
{ After  4.gxf5  dxc2-+  ,  White is forced to sacrifice the knight to avoid promotion. }
4... Bxb2 { White can resign in view of: } 5. Rxb2 Rc1+ 6. Ke2 Rxg1 *

