[SetUp "1"]

{ This is a typical structure resulting from 9.Bxf6: Black has an isolated pawn on h7 and the doubled pawns on the f-file. Strategically speaking, we are worse, so Black must find dynamics by opening the long diagonal and the center. This can be a good exercise on how to improve your most unhappy piece. }
1... e4 2. Bxe4 f5 { Sacrificing the second pawn to hit b2. } 3. Bxf5 Bxb2
{ The double attack wins the game. } 4. O-O Bxf5
{ 4...Bxa1  5.Rxa1  Qf6  is also possible, but @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/5p1p/p2p4/1p1P1B1Q/8/N7/PbP2PPP/R4RK1 b kq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bxa3?  would spell disaster after  5.Rfe1+  Kf8  6.Qh6+  Kg8  7.Bxc8  Qxc8  8.Re3+-  . }
5. Qxf5 Bxa3
{ Gaining a piece is better than having an extra exchange; it is a simple math calculation: @@StartBracket@@N=3, R-B=5-3=2@@EndBracket@@. Even though the black king is exposed, we win due to the extra material. }
