Qb1
{ The 'twin'  1...Qe4  works well too.  2.Qd1   2.Rxe4??  Rb1+  3.Qd1  Rxd1+  4.Re1  Rxe1  2...Qxe1+!  3.Qxe1  c3  ,  Black sacrificed the queen to have the time to push this strong pawn; ...c2 is coming next.  4.Qe4  ,  pay attention to the opponent's counterplay. You should always ask yourself what is the enemy's plan and what every move changes in the position.   4.Rxc3??  Rxc3  5.Qxc3  Rb1+  6.Qe1  Rxe1  4...Rb1+!  ,  luring the queen on b1 to close its diagonal.  5.Qxb1  c2  6.Qxc2  Rxc2-+  and White cannot equalize material with Rxa3 due to ...Rc1#, so Black wins. }
2. Re3 { 2.Rxb1??  Rxb1+  3.Qd1  Rxd1  is the famous back-rank mate. } 2... Bc5
