[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Tactics"]
[Black "Attack against the king #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1r1k/5bbp/p2p4/1p1Nnp2/4p3/2P1N3/PPB1QPPP/3R1RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ As usual, Black has the bishop pair and more space thanks to the central pawns. Is there anything immediate? }
1... Nf3+
{ Sacrificing the knight to destroy White's castle and create some play on the light squares. }
2. gxf3
{ 2.Kh1  Qh4  3.gxf3  Bh5  4.Ng2  Qh3  5.Ndf4  ,  White seems to be holding, but Black doesn't want to give mate anymore; it is the moment to win material.  5...exf3!  A vital move, otherwise, the black queen would be captured without compensation.  6.Nxh3  fxe2  is a nice fork.  7.Nhf4  exf1=Q+  8.Rxf1  Bf3-+  and with an extra exchange, Black is leading. }
2... Bh5 { Preparing a skewer with ...Bxf3. } 3. Ng4
{ White gives back the piece to avoid the opponent's plan. } 3... Be5
{ There's no hurry to take back the knight; it is preferable to bring all the pieces against the king.   After  3...fxg4?  4.f4  ,  White closes the position and is better. }
4. f4
{ Closing the dark-squared bishop diagonal but sacrificing the exchange.   4.Kh1  exf3  5.Qxf3  Bxg4  6.Qd3  Bxd1  7.Rxd1-+  and White does not have enough compensation for the exchange.   4.Nxe5  dxe5  5.Ne3  Qh4  ,  threatening both ...Bxf3 and ...Rg8+.  6.Ng4  is the thematic defensive idea.  6...Rae8  ,  Black would like to play ...exf3 followed by ...Bxg4, but Qxe5+ is a problem. So defends e5 first. Azel Chua calls this 'reciprocal thinking' in his Chessable course.  7.fxe4   7.Kh1  exf3  8.Qe3  Bxg4-+  Bxg4  8.f3  Bh3  Black is only a pawn down but has a great attack. }
4... Bxg4 5. f3 Bxf3 6. Rxf3 exf3 7. Qxf3 Bg7
{ The material advantage is decisive. } *

