[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Thematic Tactics"]
[Black "Facing Qxd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/5p1p/2nQbqp1/p3p3/1pP1P2P/6P1/PPN2PB1/R3K2R b KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is one of the essential ideas to learn: the d6-pawn is usually a weakness in the Sveshnikov because it is backward, so Black prefers to sacrifice it to get the initiative. White has just played Qxd6; how to respond? }
1... Rac8 { Defending the knight and preparing ...Rfd8. } 2. Qd3
{ 2.Ne3  Rfd8  3.Qc5   3.Nd5  Qg7  ,  Black does not get distracted by the knight on d5, goes away with the queen, and keeps the threat of ...Rxd6.  4.Ne7+  Nxe7  5.Qxe7  Rd7  6.Qg5  Rxc4-+  ,  Black wins back the pawn and has a splendid activity thanks to the rooks.  3...Nd4  ,  attacking the queen and adding pressure on c4.  4.Qb6  Qe7  ,  Black doesn't want to capture on c4 but opts for the queen hunting.  5.O-O  Rb8  6.Qxa5  Ra8  7.Qxe5  ,  Black sacrifices the third pawn!  7...f6  and White's queen has no more squares.  8.Nd5  Rxd5  9.Qxe6+  Qxe6  10.exd5  Qb6-+  . }
2... Bxc4 3. Qxc4 Nd4
{ Black attacks the queen and hits c2. There's no way to stop the knight fork with ...Nxc2+. }
4. Qd3 Nxc2+ *

