[Black "Shubh Jayesh Laddha − Tea Gueci, Budapest 2022 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4r1k1/4n1p1/2qpp1Np/1p2p2P/1P2P3/2P2QP1/5PK1/3R4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We finished the examples from the theoretical section of the course; now it's time for two of my games! I know this tactic blow is for White, while the course is from Black's side, but being aware of the opponent's threat is also essential.  I played a closed tournament in Budapest against this Indian guy who has now reached 2400. I thought the position was equal, and when my guard was down, my opponent went on a quest for the advantage. }
1. Qf8+
{ I still remember that in the same playing hall, there was the GM closed tournament, where an Uzbek IM was competing. He stopped by my board and looked at the position; his face was surprised. One second later, my opponent found this beautiful combination. }
1... Kh7 { After  1...Rxf8??  2.Nxe7+  Kh7  3.Nxc6+-  , White wins material. }
2. Nxe7 Qxe4+ { Thanks to this intermediate move, Black doesn't lose a piece. }
3. Qf3 { The only way to save the queen. } 3... Qxf3+ 4. Kxf3 Rxe7 5. Rxd6
{ White enters a favorable rook endgame. Even though the material is equal, Black is in trouble because the pawns are very weak. }
5... Rc7 6. Rd3
{ It was essential to keep the c3-pawn alive to support b4. And that's why, even if this is the middlegame section of an opening course, I strongly recommend studying endgames too.   6.Ke4?  Luckily, my opponent was low on time and blundered.  6...Rxc3  7.Kxe5  Rf3  8.Rd2  Rf5+  9.Kxe6  Rxh5  and the game ended in a draw.   6.Rxe6?  Rxc3+  7.Kg2  Rc4  8.Rxe5  Rxb4=  ,  with equal chances. }
*

