[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Misratdin Iskandarov − Gukesh Dommaraju, Baku 2023"]
[Result "*"]

{ I picked this game because it is very recent and an excellent example of how Black takes the initiative on the kingside, even though White has already expanded on the queenside. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 Nxd5 8.
exd5 Nb8 9. a4 { Nowadays, it is much more popular than  9.c4  . } 9... Be7 10.
Bd2 O-O 11. a5 a6
{ Usually, I prefer to wait for this move because the knight is misplaced on b5 and has to retreat anyway.   11...Nd7  is my suggestion in this position and Nakamura's pick against Nepo.  12.Bb4  e4⇆  leads to exciting complications. }
12. Na3 Bf5
{ 12...f5?!  You can think that pushing the pawn is more logical in this structure, but we will have many problems developing the light-squared bishop then. After  13.Nc4  Nd7  14.Be2  e4  15.g3  Ne5  16.Nb6  Rb8  17.h4±  ,  White controls the position very well and has much potential on the queenside, while Black has difficulties making progress. }
13. Nc4 Nd7 14. Bb4 Rc8
{ Going through the course, you will often find the sacrifice of the d6-pawn to obtain a significant advantage in development and attack the white king. }
15. Be2
{ Both captures Nxd6 and Bxd6 fail to ...Rxc2:  15.Nxd6?  Rxc2  16.Bd3  Bxd3  17.Qxd3  Rxb2-+  .   15.Bxd6?  Rxc4!  16.Bxc4  @@StartBracket@@  16.Bxe7  Re4+  17.Be2  Qxe7-+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@3q1rk1/1p1nbppp/p2B4/P2Ppb2/2B5/8/1PP2PPP/R2QK2R b KQ - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Bxd6  17.O-O  e4-+  . }
15... Bg6 { Freeing the path for the f-pawn. } 16. O-O
{ ➢  16.Nxd6?  Again, this move is a mistake.  16...Bxc2!  17.Qc1   17.Qd2  Bg5  18.Nxc8  Bxd2+  19.Kxd2  Qg5+  20.Kxc2  Rxc8+-+   17.Nxc8  Bxb4+  This intermediate move is very important.  18.Kf1  Bxd1  19.Rxd1  Qxc8-+  .  17...Bg6  18.Qe3  @@StartBracket@@  18.Nxc8  Bxb4+  19.Kf1  Qxc8-+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/1p1nbppp/p2N2b1/P2Pp3/1B6/4Q3/1P2BPPP/R3K2R b KQ - 3 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Nf6  19.Qxe5  Ne8  20.Nxc8  Bxb4+  21.Kf1  Qxc8-+  .   ➢  16.Ra3  transposes to the game after  16...Nc5  17.O-O  f5  . }
16... Nc5
{ The first new move, according to the Online Database. Black protects d6 and improves the knight.   16...Rc7!?  was played in a high-level game:  17.Ra3  f5  ,  always sacrificing the pawn on d6!  18.Bxd6  Bxd6  19.Nxd6  b5!  20.Nxb5   20.axb6?  Nxb6  ,  the knight on d6 doesn't have squares. Black is winning on the spot:  21.Rxa6  Qxd6-+  .  20...axb5  21.d6  Ra7  22.Bxb5∞  and White has a lot of compensation with three pawns for the piece. If Black cannot generate a strong attack on the kingside, there will be a free queen for White on the other side of the board.  22...Nf6  23.b4  Qb8!   23...f4?  24.c4±  1-0 Fedoseev-Gelfand, PNWCC Online blitz 2020.  24.c4  Rd8  25.d7  e4  26.Qd4  f4  27.a6  Bf5=  followed by ...Bxd7, should be fine for Black. }
17. Ra3 f5 18. Nb6
{ 18.f3  represents a standard way to stop Black's majority.  18...Rc7  19.Be1   19.Kh1  Bh5  20.Be1  e4!  ,  creating problems in the opponent's position.  21.b4  Nd7  22.fxe4  fxe4!  This move is possible thanks to the mate on the first rank.  23.Rxf8+  Qxf8  24.Ne3  @@StartBracket@@  24.Bxh5??  Qf1  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@5qk1/1prnb1pp/p2p4/P2P3b/1P2p3/R3N3/2P1B1PP/3QB2K b - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Bxe2  25.Qxe2  Bg5⇆  @@StartFEN@@3q1rk1/1pr1b1pp/p2p2b1/P1nPpp2/2N5/R4P2/1PP1B1PP/3QBRK1 b - - 2 19@@EndFEN@@  19...Nd7  20.b4  f4  21.c3  Nf6  22.Nb6  e4∞  The position becomes messy, as Black likes. }
18... Rc7 19. Bxc5
{ This is a very critical decision that I don't like for White because he gives up the bishop pair too early.   19.c4!?  is the standard way to proceed on the queenside. Probably, White was scared that the knight could retreat to d7 and move on to the kingside, helping the attack.  19...Nd7  ,  Black returns with the knight in view of White's plan with Bc3 followed by b4.  20.Nxd7   20.Na4  e4  21.f3  ,  it is necessary to prevent Black's expansion.   21.Be1?  If White plays too passively, he can be immediately punished by a strong attack.  21...f4  ,  the pawns are rolling, and White's king is more scared move after move.  22.f3  Ne5  23.Rc3  exf3  24.gxf3  Re8∓  and now that the e-file is open, Black tries to conquer it and is better.  21...exf3  22.Raxf3  Ne5  23.Rc3  f4↑  .  The typical resulting situation from this structure: White manages to push c5 while Black goes for the attack on the kingside.  20...Qxd7  21.h3   21.Bc3  ,  the human plan to break with b4 and c5 is too slow.  21...e4  22.b4  f4⇆  ,  the position remains complicated, but I like Black's chances on the kingside. I think it is better to have the opponent's king as the main target of the position instead of some pawns...  21...f4  22.f3⩲  ,  White stops Black's plan and is slightly better. Without a black knight on the board, the weakness on g3 is ineffective. }
19... Rxc5 20. b4 Rc7 21. c4 e4
{ Iskandarov has exchanged the dark-squared bishop, so we have to open up the position and maximize the strength of our pieces. }
22. f4 exf3 23. Bxf3 Bf6 24. Kh1
{ White secures the king from potential checks on the dark squares.   24.c5!?  starts a very concrete plan that only engines can think about.  24...dxc5  25.d6  Bd4+  26.Kh1  Qxd6  ,  it seems that White has lost two pawns without compensation, but the pin on the bishop on d4 is quite annoying for Black.  27.Rd3  Rd8  28.bxc5  Rxc5  29.Nd5!  It interferes with the defense of the bishop.  29...Rxd5  30.Bxd5+  Qxd5  31.Rf4  Qxa5  32.Rfxd4  Rxd4  33.Rxd4  h6=  and even if Black is up on the material, the engine evaluates the position as equal. I think that Black has much more practical chances thanks to the connected passed pawns. }
24... Be5 25. Re1 Rcf7 { Redirecting the forces to the kingside. } 26. Rae3
{ According to the engine, this move is dubious, but I think the position was already difficult to handle.   26.g3  is the only move to maintain equality. White should have restrained Gukesh's initiative on the kingside.  26...f4  27.g4  Qh4  28.c5  Re7↑  and  Stockfish's 16 says it is balanced, but from a human perspective, everything can happen. }
26... Bf4 { The Indian prodigy plays in a highly accurate way! } 27. Qd4
{ White will not have enough compensation for the exchange.   27.Re6?!  Qh4  28.h3  Rc7!  With the idea of ...Bf7, Black has a winning position.  29.Qd4  Bf7  30.R6e2  Qg3  31.Kg1  g5-+  .   27.R3e2  occupies the square where the king will run away from the checks.  27...Qh4  28.h3  Rc7-+  ,  a prophylactic idea to avoid White's counterplay with c5 and free the f7-square for the bishop to push ...g5-g4.   27.c5  seems to be the best chance not to have a decisive disadvantage. White must find an activity to try to compensate for the exchange. After  27...Bxe3  28.Rxe3  f4  29.Re6  dxc5  30.bxc5  Rc7∓  ,  Black is better thanks to the material imbalance, but the position still requires accurate play. }
27... Bxe3 28. Qxe3 f4 29. Qe6 Bf5 30. Qe2 Qh4 31. Kg1 Qf6
{ Black anticipates Qf2 and goes away with the queen to enter with ...Qd4+ or ...Qc3. }
32. Qd2 Re7 { Black is ultimately winning both materially and dynamically. }
33. Rxe7 Qxe7 34. c5 dxc5 35. d6 Qe3+
{ Destroying White's chances to strike back. } 36. Qxe3 fxe3 37. bxc5 Be4
{ Exploiting the strength of the passed pawn on e3. } 38. Bg4
{ 38.Bxe4?  e2  and promotion is unavoidable. } 38... Bd3 39. Bf3 Be4 40. Bg4
Kf7 { Gukesh brings the last piece into play. } 41. Nc4 Kf6 42. Nxe3 Ke5
{ Sacrificing the e3-pawn to eliminate c5 from the board. } 43. Nc4+ Kd4 44.
Nb6 Bc6
{ Black avoids the trick:  44...Kxc5  45.Nd7+  and Iskandarov resigned. This was one of the latest examples of Sveshnikov's power. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Vassily Ivanchuk − Kacper Piorun, Matanzas 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ Please don't get fooled by the first move, we will reach the Sveshnikov anyway! }
1... c5 2. e4
{ Transposing to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  . }
2... Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 Nxd5 8. exd5 Nb8 9.
c4 { This is the old main line. Nowadays,  9.a4  is played more. } 9... Nd7
{ 9...Be7  − in my opinion, it's preferable to start with the development of the kingside, basically for two reasons: first of all, Black is more flexible and can decide later on how to play on the queenside, and secondly, it's better to be faster with the counterplay against the opponent's king.  10.Be2  O-O  11.O-O  a6  ,  including this move is also essential because White has the annoying c5 break otherwise.  12.Nc3  f5  is my suggestion in the theoretical part of the course. }
10. Be2
{ 10.Bd3  Be7  11.O-O  O-O  12.Qc2!⩲  and now it's much more challenging to play ...f5; the knight on d7 has to be moved again. }
10... Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Kh1
{ Preparing to push the f-pawn without being attacked. } 12... f5
{ This position with the bishop on e2 is not dangerous for Black because our play is straightforward: ...a6-a5, ...b6, ...f4, ...g5. }
13. f3
{ 13.f4  a6!  Without this move, Black couldn't play ...Bf6 because of Nxd6.  14.Nc3  Bf6  15.Be3  exf4!  The standard reaction in this structure.  16.Bxf4  Ne5=  ,  our position is beautiful once we reach the e5-square with the 'octopus' knight. }
13... a6 14. Nc3 Bg5 { Another typical plan is exchanging the bad bishop. } 15.
b4 b6 { Restraining White's growth on the queenside. } 16. a3 Ra7
{ It's an intelligent way to bring the other rook to the kingside. } 17. Bxg5
Qxg5 18. Qc1 Qd8
{ 18...Qxc1  was possible, but I prefer the move played in the game because it keeps the attack alive with the queens on the board.  19.Rfxc1  Kf7  ,  the king is running to protect the d6-pawn because Black will often need to play ...a5 to stop White's expansion on the queenside, but in doing so, the b5-square is left to the white knight.  20.a4   20.Kg1  Ke7  21.Kf2  g5⇆   20.Na4  Rc7  21.Rc3  Bb7  22.Rac1  Rfc8=  20...Rb7!  This is a crucial move that prevents the a5 break from White.  21.Rcb1   21.a5  bxa5  22.bxa5  @@StartBracket@@  22.Rxa5?  Rxb4∓  is the idea behind ...Rb7.  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2b2r2/1r3kpp/p2p4/P1nPpp2/2P5/2N2P2/4B1PP/R1R4K w - - 1 23@@EndFEN@@  22...Nc5⩱  21...a5  22.Nb5  Ke7⩱  ,  Black defends the pawn and has a slight edge thanks to the pawn play on the kingside. }
19. Qe3 f4 20. Qf2 Nf6
{ According to the engine, White is slightly better here, but in a practical game, Black is doing fine and can win many games with the usual attack. }
21. Rfd1
{ Ivanchuk is playing too slow and leaves Piorun the initiative.   21.a4!  Pushing the majority on the queenside and preparing a5 followed by c5.  21...Raf7  22.a5   22.c5  bxc5  23.bxc5  Qa5  24.Rac1  dxc5∞  22...bxa5  23.Rxa5  g5  ,  Black is ready to counterattack!  24.c5  g4  ,  reaching a very similar King's Indian type of position: if White does not get mated, we will win on the queenside. Otherwise, we will get the whole point.  25.Bxa6   25.c6?  g3!  26.hxg3  Nh5  27.gxf4  exf4-+  25...Bf5∞  ,  with an unclear position, open to three results. }
21... g5 { Launching the pawns against the opponent's king. } 22. Na4 Rg7
{ Piorun sacrifices the b6-pawn to proceed with the attack on the other side of the board. }
23. Nxb6
{ More resilient was:  23.Qxb6  Qe7  ,  avoiding the queen's exchange.  24.c5  Qe8  25.Nc3   25.Bxa6  Bf5  and ...g4 is coming next.  @@StartBracket@@Instead,  25...Qxa4??  26.Bxc8  Rxc8  27.Qxd6+-  ,  when White penetrates our defenses and is winning.  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@4qrk1/6rp/BQ1p1n2/2PPpbp1/NP3p2/P4P2/6PP/R2R3K w - - 0 26@@EndFEN@@  26.Nc3   26.Qxd6  g4!  Black doesn't lose time to capture the knight on a4 but goes for the 'big fish'.  27.Bd3  Bxd3  28.Rxd3  e4!  It's the only crushing move. Black has three pawns down and must continue the attack on the kingside and destroy the enemy's barriers as soon as possible.  29.fxe4  Nxe4  30.Qe6+  Qxe6  31.dxe6  Nf2+  32.Kg1  Nxd3-+  .  26...g4  27.Bd3   27.fxg4?!  Nxg4  28.cxd6  Nxh2!  A recurrent motif in this game. White's king is left alone without defenders, and Black is looking for a mate.  29.Kg1   29.Kxh2  ,  can you find a mate in ten?  29...Qh5+  30.Kg1  f3  31.Ra2  fxg2  32.Kf2  Bd3+  33.Ke1  Qh6  ,  creating a cage for the white king. Mate is unavoidable.  Or  33...g1=Q+  34.Qxg1  Rxg1+  35.Kd2  Rxd1+  36.Nxd1  Bxa6-+  .  29...Qh5-+  .  27...Bxd3  28.Rxd3  e4!  The key to the victory.  29.fxe4  g3  30.Rf3  Qh5  31.h3  Ng4-+  and  White can resign.  25...g4  26.Rd2  Qh5  27.c6  g3  28.Qg1  Qh6-+  ,  Black's attack is destructive. }
23... Bf5 { Preserving the bishop and supporting both ...e4 and ...g4. } 24.
Bd3 Bxd3 25. Rxd3 g4 { Black's attack is unstoppable. } 26. c5
{ White is too slow. } 26... g3
{ 26...e4!  was probably more potent, but even the text move is correct.  27.Rc3  e3  28.Qe2  Nh5-+  . }
27. Qe1 gxh2
{ I don't appreciate this capture because the h2-pawn is now a shield for the white king. }
28. Qh4 Qe8 { 28...e4  was the cue of the game.  29.Rb3  Kh8-+  . } 29. c6 Nh5
{ Getting closer to the enemy. } 30. Nd7 Ng3+ 31. Kxh2 Rf5
{ Preparing ...Rxd7 followed by ...Rh5. } 32. Re1 Rxd7
{ The final blow, eliminating the threat of Nf6+.   32...Rh5??  fails to  33.Nf6+  Kh8  34.Qxh5+-  . }
33. Qg4+
{ 33.cxd7  Qxd7  34.Kg1  Qc7-+  ,  threatening ...Rh5-h1 followed by ...Qc2+. }
33... Rg7
{ This was not a perfect game; both players made some little inaccuracies, which is why it is so interesting. It is symbolic of the structures resulting from @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nd5  .  White tried to achieve the c5 break. Meanwhile, Black assaulted the kingside with ...f5 and ...g5. Usually, whoever is faster wins, exactly as Piorun did. }
