[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Monika Motycakova − Tea Gueci, Radenci 2019"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played in the first round of the Mitropa Cup 2019. For the first time in my life, I was Italy's board 1. Before going to the tournament hall, I reassured my teammates to be confident even if I had three pawns less and that it was a deep home prep. I particularly like this line because it forced me not to be materialistic anymore. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Bxf6
{ White gives the bishop pair to destroy Black's structure. The general consensus is that Black's activity compensates for the structural weaknesses. }
9... gxf6 10. Nd5 Bg7
{ If you remember the theoretical section, this is the Novosibirsk Variation, and the second most played variation after  10...f5  . }
11. Bd3 Ne7 { Fighting the opponent's number one. } 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. O-O O-O
14. c4 f5
{ I repeatedly wrote that when White pushes the c-pawn in this particular structure, Black must quickly react with ...f5 to avoid Nc2-e3-f5 and create counterplay. }
15. Qh5
{ Putting pressure on h7.   The most popular is  15.Qf3  Qb7!?  16.exf5  Qxf3  17.gxf3  e4!  Sacrificing the second pawn.  18.Bxe4   18.fxe4?  Bxb2  19.Nc2  Bxa1  20.Rxa1  bxc4  21.Bxc4  Bb7-+  18...d5!  You may find this theme in the Typical Structures & Ideas chapter as 'pawns don't count, activity does!'.  19.Bxd5  Rb8   19...Bxf5!?  is interesting, but I consider ...Rb8 as the main line, not to sacrifice too much material.  20.Bxa8  Rxa8  21.cxb5  Bxb2  22.Nc4  Bxa1  23.Rxa1  axb5  24.Nd6  Bd3  25.Rd1  Ra3  26.Rd2  Kg7  27.Rb2  Ra6  28.Nxb5  Bxb5  29.Rxb5  Rxa2  30.Kg2  Kg6  31.Rb6+  Kg7  32.Rb5  Kg6  33.Rb6+  Kg7  34.Rb5  ½-½ Sarana-Dubov, Satka 2018.  20.Rad1  Bxb2  21.Nc2  Bxf5  ,  bothering the white pieces.  22.Ne3  Bh3  23.Rfe1  Bc3  24.Re2  Rfc8=  and Black has compensation for the pawn thanks to the bishop pair. }
15... Rb8 16. exf5 e4 17. Rae1 Bb7
{ It rarely happens to have more time on the clock at move seventeen than when you started. It is necessary to defend the pawn. }
18. Qg4 { Pinning the bishop and adding an attacker to the e4-pawn. } 18...
Rfe8 { 18...bxc4?  19.Bxe4± } 19. cxb5
{ Till this moment, we both blitzed, but after my move, she started a long thinking. }
19... Kh8
{ I was happy because there were no OTB games with  19...Kh8  , only correspondence or email chess. My opponent was surprised even though she was an expert on the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/5ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p1B1/4P3/N1N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq b6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Bxf6  line.  The idea of ...Kh8 is to solve the pin of the bishop and free the g8-square for the rook. }
20. bxa6
{ White has three extra pawns. Can you imagine the shocked faces of my teammates looking at this position? Would you think that Black is doing fine? }
20... Ba8
{ The bishop on a8 is a good blocker, and White's pawns go nowhere. After half an hour of reflection, she made one of the few moves not in my opening file. }
21. b3
{ I knew this must be a mistake. White cannot be too greedy and should activate the pieces, especially the knight on a3 that is out of play. This is the reason why Nb5 is the best move.   The best option is  21.Nb5  d5  ,  Black has to defend e4 and occupy the center. The bishop pair, the solid central pawns, and the attacking prospects on the kingside give compensation.  22.a7  Rb6  23.a4  Be5  ,  Black is ready to bring both rooks to the attack and has full equality.  24.f4  Bxb2  and despite the two pawns less, Black has a slight edge given by the activity of the pieces and the two connected central passed pawns. }
21... d5
{ I immediately responded with ...d5 because it was the correct move against all White's options. It defends the center and attacks the white knight, which is now undefended because of the previous b3. }
22. Nb5
{ Compared to @@StartFEN@@br2r2k/4qpbp/P2p4/5P2/4p1Q1/N2B4/PP3PPP/4RRK1 w - - 1 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Nb5  , the difference is that Black cannot take back a pawn  with ...Bxb2 but has an extra tempo to attack the kingside.   22.Nc2  Rbc8  ,  Black stops Be2 by putting pressure on c2. After  23.Qd1  Rg8-+  ,  White is stuck and has no way to improve the position. }
22... Rg8
{ If  22...Be5  23.Be2  Rg8  24.Qh5  d4-+  , we reach the same position as after 22...Rg8. }
23. Qh5 { 23.--  Be5  24.Qh5  exd3  winning a piece. } 23... Rb6
{ A rook lift to prepare a rook shift! } 24. f6
{ This can be thematic, but it is more effective when White can exploit the f5-square @@StartBracket@@clearance sacrifice@@EndBracket@@ or capture d5.   Following  24.g3  Rxa6  25.Bb1  Rh6  26.Qe2  Qg5  ,  the white knight is out of play, dominated by the dark-squared bishop.  27.f4  Qxf5-+  and Black has only one pawn less, while our attack is crushing; ...Rg6, ...h5-h4 are coming next. }
24... Rxf6 25. Be2
{ 25.Re3  Rh6  26.Qf5  Be5  ,  hitting h2.  27.f4   27.h3  Rhg6  ,  after provoking h3, Black puts pressure on g2.  28.g4  Rg5-+  trapping the queen.  27...Bb8-+  ,  with the two bishops on the back rank, Black is ready to push the central pawns and assault White's castle. }
25... Rxa6
{ Being a team competition, I tried to gain back material, but this was not the best attitude.   25...Rh6  was stronger.  26.Qf5  Be5  27.g3  Qh4  ,  Black temporarily sacrifices.  28.Qxe5+  f6  29.Qh5  Rxh5  30.Bxh5  Qxh5-+  and the material advantage is decisive. }
26. Rc1
{ After  26.Nd4  26...Rg6  27.Nf5  Qe6  28.g3  Be5-+  ,  White has no chance. }
26... Be5 27. a4 { White is too slow to push the pawns. } 27... Rag6
{ Forcing g3. } 28. g3 d4
{ Now that the long diagonal is weak, Black must open the path for the forgotten bishop on a8. }
29. Qh3 Bd5
{ It's not the best choice, but it's still correct.  29...Qb7!?  30.Qg2  d3  31.Bd1  Qb6-+  and our pawns are unstoppable! }
30. Bc4 { 30.Rc8  d3  31.Rxg8+  Rxg8  32.Bd1  Be6  33.Qh6  f5-+ } 30... Bb7
{ 30...Ba8-+  ,  coming back to a8 was even more potent. } 31. Rfe1 e3
{ My opponent resigned because of ...exf2+ and the tactical ideas with ...Bxg3. I'm not sure if this is one of the best games of my career because I was prepared till move 21, so it's like I played only ten moves to win... But it is a perfect demonstration of how useful it is to study not only the theory but also the plans and the structures of the opening.  It is also a model of the principle: material doesn't always count, the relative value of the pieces does. White had three extra pawns, but the pieces lacked coordination, while Black's bishop pair was perfectly organized with the major pieces. }
