[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Sergio Braghetta − Tea Gueci, Sicilian League 2023"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played during the Italian second league, the so-called 'A.1', where my Sicilian team, 'Pedone Isolano'  (Isolated Pawn)  , won the tournament, qualifying for the major league. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c3
{ The Sveshnikov's main line is considered more strategic than  11.c4  and probably the most critical together with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/1N2p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nd5  . }
11... Rb8
{ I didn't play for a long time, so I was a bit 'rusty' and forgot about the best move order.  11...O-O  12.Nc2  Rb8  is what we should play, as analyzed in the theoretical section. }
12. Nc2 Bg5
{ The difference with 11...O-O is that a4 is now suitable for White because Black's king is still in the center. }
13. Be2
{ After  13.a4  bxa4  14.Ncb4  Nxb4  15.Nxb4  Bd7  ,  can you spot the differences? Black's bishop is on g5 rather than f6, and the king is on e8 rather than castled.  16.Bxa6  Qa5  is a complicated and double-edged line that, with accurate play, leads to a balanced position. }
13... O-O 14. O-O
{ Transposing to the correct move order: @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/5ppp/p1np1b2/1p1Np3/4P3/N7/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.c3  O-O  12.Nc2  Rb8  13.Be2  Bg5  . }
14... Be6
{ The second most popular according to the Online Database, where I suggest  14...a5  .  The idea is to avoid Ncb4, but it is not the only enjoyable move. }
15. Bf3
{ I was surprised by Bf3 because it seemed a waste of time; it doesn't help in the fight for d5 because, having the e4-pawn, the bishop cannot directly defend the knight. It is a novelty in OTB chess; there's only an email game between intermediate players.   15.Qd3  a5  16.Nce3  Ne7  transposes to the theoretical part of the course. }
15... g6
{ I quickly responded with ...g6 to give space to the king and slowly improve the position. When the opponents show that they have unclear ideas about what to do, these 'mini moves' are the best strategy. }
16. Qd3 Kh8 17. Rfd1
{ When the enemy's rook is on the same file as our queen, we should always go away from it. I was unsure about placing it on d7 or c8. From c8, the queen can go to c5 and protect the a6-pawn when White plays Ncb4, while d7 defends d6. In the end, I thought the first option was more multifunctional. }
17... Qc8 18. Qe2
{ 18.Ncb4  Nxb4  19.cxb4  Qc4  is another idea of ...Qc8.  20.g3  Qxd3  21.Rxd3  Rfc8⩱  and thanks to the bishop pair, Black has a slight edge. }
18... Rd8
{ I opted for a more wait-and-see approach. It was more accurate to start the minority attack on the queenside immediately:  18...a5  19.h3  Ne7  ,  fighting the opponent's number one.  20.Nxe7  Bxe7  21.Ne3  21...Qc5⩱  . }
19. Nce3
{ Now that all of Black's pieces are well-placed, it is time to begin the action. }
19... b4
{ Since the white knight is not on c2 anymore, I decided to create weaknesses with ...b4, followed by ...bxc3. }
20. Nc4
{ The more I look at this position, the more I Iove the Sveshnikov: Black has the bishop pair and will soon open lines and create problems on the queenside.   20.Bg4  bxc3  21.bxc3  ,  the queenside break caused White two isolated pawns.  21...Kg7  22.Rab1  Rxb1  23.Rxb1  Bxe3  24.Bxe6  Bxf2+  ,  Black wins a pawn in the complications,  25.Qxf2  Qxe6=  . }
20... bxc3 21. bxc3 Ne7
{ Putting pressure on the light squares, in particular on the c4-knight. The white bishop is not helpful. }
22. Rab1
{ 22.g3  is Stockfish 16's favorite, but from a human perspective, it makes no sense if you are worried about the action on the other side of the board. After  22...Qc5  23.h4  Bh6  24.Nce3  Nxd5  25.Nxd5  Rb7⩱  ,  Black is slightly better thanks to the bishop pair and significant coordination. }
22... Qc5
{ 22...Rxb1!?  is even more precise. It was hard for me to understand if including the rook exchange was an accuracy during the game.  23.Rxb1  Qc5  24.Ncb6  Nxd5  25.Nxd5  Bxd5  26.exd5⩱  ,  reaching the exact position of the game, with a pair of rooks less. It is preferable according to the engine, but I didn't want to leave White the b-file. }
23. Ncb6
{ Black will change the structure into Sveshnikov type 3 @@StartBracket@@Najdorf type 1@@EndBracket@@ with the white pawn on d5. As you probably remember, every time that White is forced to capture with a pawn rather than having a piece on d5, it is a victory for Black.   More resilient was  23.Rxb8  Rxb8  24.Nde3  Rd8  25.g3  h5⩱  . }
23... Nxd5 24. Nxd5 Bxd5
{ Once again, the engine prefers to include the exchange of the rooks.  24...Rxb1  25.Rxb1  Bxd5  26.exd5  transposing to 22...Rxb1.  26...Qxc3  27.Qxa6  Bc1∓  . }
25. exd5
{ The right moment to stop and reassess the position: the structure has changed, and many pieces are not on the board anymore. I suggest you reevaluate the situation every time something changes: pawn chain, trade of pieces, the transition from the middlegame to the endgame...  With the opposite-colored bishops, only the player with the initiative and more attacking chances can hope to win. White has three pawn islands, while Black only has two; the white bishop is blocked by the pawn and has no way to improve; the black one can benefit from the typical maneuver ...Bd8-b6-c5. What to do with the pawns on c3 and a5 that are hanging?   This is the difference with trading on b1 or not:  25.Rxb8  Rxb8  26.Rxd5  Qxc3  27.Qxa6  Rb2⩱  .  I overestimated this position during the game. I was happy to place a rook on the second rank and not afraid of White's counterplay. However, the objective evaluation is that White can still fight for the draw with accurate play. }
25... a5
{ Of course, Black should play against the weakness on c3 and not exchange pawns to avoid drawish endgames. }
26. c4 Rb4 { Taking more space on the open file. } 27. Rxb4
{ I remember that I was unsure if it was better to capture with the queen and try to exploit the b-file or make it semi-open to put pressure on the a2-weakness. Then I thought about my game against IM Olga Zimina, where I threw away my advantage by mismanaging a similar situation with an open file and picked the second option. The experience made me make the right decision. }
27... axb4
{ 27...Qxb4!?  28.Qc2  Rb8  29.g3  Kg7  30.h4  Bd8  31.c5!  White sacrifices a pawn to force Black to occupy the c5-square with a pawn.  31...Qa3  32.Rd3  Qxc5  33.Qxc5  dxc5∓  and Black still has an advantage, but it is more challenging to convert. }
28. Qc2 Rc8 { Freeing the d8-square for the bishop with tempo, attacking c4. }
29. Be2 Bd8 { The typical Sicilian maneuver. } 30. Qb2 Bb6
{ The difference between the two bishops is evident: the white one is passive and blocked by the pawns, while the black one is actively attacking f2 and creating weaknesses in the enemy's territory. }
31. Bf1 Qa5 32. Rb1 Bc5 33. Qd2 Ra8 { Putting pressure on the isolated pawn. }
34. Rb2 Kg7 { 34...Qa3  35.Rc2  Kg7-+ } 35. g3 Bd4
{ The bishop becomes a monster. } 36. Rc2 Qc5
{ Black prepares to bring the rook with ...Ra3. } 37. h4 Ra3 38. Kg2
{ 38.--  Rxg3+  39.Bg2  Qc8-+ } 38... e4
{ Here I spent plenty of time. I was aware that the pawn push is strategically speaking somewhat dubious since it leaves the bishop less protected, but it is the time for the final sprint: Black must disrupt the opponent's defense with ...e4-e3. Strategical tip: Attack the base of a pawn chain. }
39. Qe1 f5
{ After  39...e3  40.f4  Bc3  41.Qd1  Bd2-+  ,  Black is winning, but I didn't go for it because I wanted to keep the rook more active. }
40. Be2 f4
{ That is the only inaccuracy I made in this game. My opponent was low on time, and I thought it was clever to create threats. It is not the best, but it is still a good practical move under these circumstances; ...f3 and ...e3 are coming next. }
41. gxf4
{ 41.Bd1  e3!  42.Bf3  @@StartBracket@@  42.fxe3  Rxe3  g3 is falling.  43.Qf1  Rxg3+  44.Kh2  Bg1+  45.Kh1  Qe3∓  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@8/6kp/3p2p1/2qP4/1pPb1p1P/r3pBP1/P1R2PK1/4Q3 b - - 1 42@@EndFEN@@  42...Qa7  and White cannot hold everything anymore:  43.fxe3  Rxa2  44.Qb1  Rxc2+  45.Qxc2  fxe3-+  . }
41... Qc8
{ Here's my geometrical idea: bringing the most potent piece to the party! }
42. f3 Qf5 43. Qd2 Be3
{ My opponent resigned because of ...Qxf4 and a crushing attack on the dark squares. I consider this one of my best games because I played patiently, slowly improving the position till the right moment to attack.  I'm pretty sure that FM Braghetta underestimated the power of the dark-squared bishop, thinking that all the positions with the opposite-colored bishops are drawn. The text shows that this is all but valid!  We discussed many themes: going from structure 1 to structure 3, playing on the queenside, creating weaknesses with pawns, maneuvering the bishop, and opposite-colored bishops. }
