[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Andre Nielsen − Tea Gueci, Stockholm 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4
{ We have this fully covered in the course. } 11... b4
{ Black rarely wants to capture on c4 − remember that White is trying to dominate the light squares. }
12. Nc2 O-O
{ It's more precise than  12...a5  because it avoids problems  with Qf3. } 13.
Bd3
{ Not the ideal square for the bishop in the structures with c4, as it cannot go to d5 via b3. }
13... a5 14. b3
{ Usually, White prefers to castle and finish development before starting play on the queenside.   14.O-O  Bg5  is analyzed in the theoretical section. }
14... g6
{ 14...Bg5  is still possible, but I wanted to avoid the lines with h4. } 15.
Nxf6+
{ White's last chance to eliminate the bishop pair. As we already know, Black is not afraid of this exchange because White gives the strong central knight. }
15... Qxf6
{ From this move on, my game is the only one in the Online Database. Even though White didn't play the most critical variations, I think that sometimes it's more useful to look at some model games played by intermediate players than the ones played by super GMs. Our moves are easier to understand and there are more mistakes to discuss. }
16. Qd2
{ White delays castling so as not to reveal their intentions and to put the rook on d1 soon.   More natural was  16.O-O  a4  17.Be2  Kg7  18.Qd2  Bb7  19.Rfd1   19.Nxb4  Nd4  ,  Black occupies the outpost and puts pressure on e4.  20.Qd3  Qf4  21.Nd5  Bxd5  22.exd5  Rfb8  and Black is leading in development.  23.Bd1  axb3  24.Bxb3  Rb4⩱  .  19...Rfb8  20.f3   20.Qxd6?!  is the start of a forcing variation that ends in Black's favor.  20...Qxd6  21.Rxd6  axb3  22.axb3  Rxa1+  23.Nxa1  Nd4  24.Bd3  Ra8  25.Nc2  Nxc2  26.Bxc2  Bxe4  ,  taking advantage of back rank's problems,  27.Bd1  Ra1⩱  .  20...axb3  21.axb3  Rxa1  22.Rxa1  Bc8  ,  with equal chances. }
16... Be6 17. h4
{ Once again, O-O was preferable. White's king is still in the center and cannot castle long − h4 weakens the kingside. }
17... h5
{ Blocking my opponent's plan.  17...a4!?  I should have started the expansion on the queenside. I consider it a minority attack because Black has two pawns versus three, but after c4 and ...b4, it is like a two vs. two.  18.Rb1  axb3  19.axb3  Ra2⩱  . }
18. Rd1
{ 18.Be2  − the bishop is better on e2 because it leaves the d-file open.  18...a4  19.O-O  axb3  20.axb3  Qxh4  21.Rxa8  Rxa8  22.Qxd6  Rc8⩱  .  Black is slightly better, but these simplifications are preferable for White rather than how the game was played. }
18... Kg7 19. Be2 Rfd8 20. g3
{ Preparing the short castle. As one of my coaches, GM Alessio Valsecchi, says: when all your pieces are doing great, it is time to push a pawn!   20.O-O ?  Qxh4∓ }
20... a4 21. O-O Bh3
{ 21...axb3  22.axb3  Ra2  23.Qc1  ,  White stops ...Rb2.  @@StartBracket@@  23.Ra1  Rda8  24.Rxa2  Rxa2  25.Ra1  Rb2-+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@3r4/5pk1/2npbqp1/4p2p/1pP1P2P/1P4P1/r1N1BP2/2QR1RK1 b - - 2 23@@EndFEN@@  23...Rda8  24.Rd2  Na5  25.Rd3  Qd8⩱  and the rook on the second rank gives Black a significative edge. }
22. Rfe1 axb3 23. axb3 Ra2
{ I thought it was more precise to enter on a2 with ...Bh3 included, but it is the opposite: with the white rook on f1 instead of e1, after Qc1, the bishop on e2 is unprotected. }
24. Ra1 Rda8 25. Qd3
{ White allows Black to start attacking the kingside.   25.Rxa2  was White's best choice.  25...Rxa2  26.Qc1  Nd4  27.Nxd4  exd4  ,  threatening ...d3.  28.Qd1  is the only move not to lose.  28...Qe5⩱  is similar to the game. }
25... Nd4
{ Usually, this is a good move, but in this case, it makes things too equal and loses the chance to create dynamics.   25...g5!  Assaulting the enemy.  26.Rxa2  Rxa2  27.hxg5  Qxg5  28.Kh2  Bd7  29.Bd1  @@StartBracket@@  29.Qxd6??  Rxc2  30.Qxd7  Nd4-+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@8/3b1pk1/2np4/4p1qp/1pP1P3/1P1Q2P1/r1N2P1K/3BR3 b - - 3 29@@EndFEN@@  29...Qf6  and Black's initiative is considerable:  30.Rf1  Nd4-+  . }
26. Rxa2 Rxa2 27. Nxd4 exd4 28. f3
{ This is dubious because it deliberately weakens g3.   28.Rd1  Bg4  29.Rd2  Rxd2  30.Qxd2  Bxe2  31.Qxe2  Qe5=  ,  with a drawish endgame. }
28... Qe5 29. f4
{ 29.Kh2?  is a mistake because it places the king on the same rank as the opponent's rook.  29...Bc8  30.Kg2  d5!!  ,  with the idea to undermine the defense of the bishop.  31.cxd5  @@StartBracket@@  31.exd5  Bf5  32.Qd1  d3-+  , the pin is fatal.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2b5/5pk1/6p1/3Pq2p/1p1pP2P/1P1Q1PP1/r3B1K1/4R3 b - - 0 31@@EndFEN@@  31...Ba6  ,  Black gains the queen:  32.Qxa6  Rxa6  33.Bxa6  d3-+  . }
29... Qc5 { My opponent made a lethal mistake. } 30. Bf1
{ The difference with Bf3 is that it allows ...Bg4, which prevents the plan with Rd1 and Qxd4. It gives Black the whole point.   30.Bf3∞  is the only move to stay in the game. The white bishop defends g2 and controls g4 simultaneously.  30...Rb2  31.Rd1  Kf8  is approximately equal. }
30... Bg4 31. Bg2 Qa7 32. Kh2 f6
{ Not the most accurate, but not a mistake. I didn't go for  32...Rb2  because I wanted to avoid e5, but it was not a problem:  33.e5  Bf5  34.Qf3  d3  35.exd6  Qd4-+  . }
33. Kh1 Ra1 34. Qd2
{ 34.Qf1  Ra2  35.e5  fxe5  36.fxe5  dxe5  37.c5  Qxc5  38.Rc1  Rc2  39.Rxc2  Qxc2-+ }
34... Qa2
{ Black plans to exchange the heavy pieces and win the endgame thanks to the difference of activity between the two bishops, the weakness on b3, and the strong pawn on d3. }
35. Qxb4 { 35.Qxa2  Rxa2  36.Bf1  Rb2  37.Ra1  Rxb3-+ } 35... Rxe1+ 36. Qxe1 d3
37. e5 d2 38. exf6+ Kxf6
{ Nielsen resigned due to unavoidable promotion. I know this is not a top-level game, but it is a good example of how to win on the queenside and how intermediate players deal with these positions. }
