{ This game was played at last year's European Women's Chess Championship. My opponent is a strong and experienced WGM. I went for my favorite opening to stay solid with Black. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4
{ I was expecting the main line with  11.c3  , so even though I knew my opening well, I started overthinking and entered time trouble. }
11... b4 12. Nc2 O-O 13. g3 a5 14. Bg2 g6
{ As suggested in the theoretical section, this is the second most popular choice: Black wants to preserve the bishop with ...Bg7. }
15. O-O
{ 15.h4  h5  ,  not necessary, but I prefer to stop White's expansion. After  16.Nxf6+  Qxf6  ,  Black gives up the bishop pair, but the strong knight on d5 disappears from the board too.   15.Nxf6+  ,  usually, White prefers to eliminate the bishop pair.  15...Qxf6  16.O-O  h5  . }
15... Bg7 16. h4
{ It is the only game with  16.h4  , which is a typical idea but with a different move order.  16.Qd3  is the most played in the Online Database,  16...Be6  . }
16... h5
{ I knew that against @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/5p1p/2np1bp1/p2Np3/1pP1P3/6P1/PPN2PBP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.h4  Black has to play  15...h5  , so I responded pretty fast in the same way. It was probably better to  prepare the ...f5 push quickly since the h5 break for White is not so dangerous, with the rook not being on h1 anymore after she  castled.  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/5pbp/2np2p1/p2Np3/1pP1P2P/6P1/PPN2PB1/R2Q1RK1 b - h3 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Kh8!  17.Nde3  @@StartBracket@@  17.Qd3  f5  18.Rad1  f4∓  ,  White regrets the late h4 after castle.  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/5pbp/2np2p1/p2Np3/1pP1P2P/6P1/PPN2PB1/R2Q1RK1 b - h3 0 16@@EndFEN@@  17...Ra6  18.h5  Qg5  ,  whenever White plays h5, Black gets the g5-square for the bishop or the queen, so it is nothing to fear;  19.hxg6  fxg6⩱  . }
17. Qd3 Be6 18. Rad1
{ Black has many exciting plans and choosing one was hard. Finally, I went for ...Qb8 with the idea of ...Rd8, ...Qa7-c5. }
18... Qb8 19. b3 a4
{ Since the queen supports the b4-pawn, Black can start play on the queenside. }
20. Kh2
{ 20.Rb1  axb3  21.axb3  Bxd5  22.exd5  Nd4  ,  entering an opposite-colored bishop middlegame with a slight edge. }
20... axb3 21. axb3 Qb7
{ ➢  21...Bxd5  is the engine's suggestion. I preferred to keep the tension.  22.Qxd5  22...Qb6  23.Qb5   23.Qxd6??  You may find such ideas in the thematic tactics section. The d6-pawn is usually poisoned.  23...Rad8  24.c5  Qb7-+  and the white queen is trapped.  23...Qc7⩱  With the tiniest edge.   ➢  21...Qa7?!  It is not correct due to Nxb4.  22.Ncxb4  Nxb4  23.Nxb4⩲ }
22. Nde3
{ She delayed the battle for the a-file to put pressure on d6. More natural to me was  22.Ra1  Bxd5  23.Qxd5  Qb6  24.Rxa8  Rxa8  25.Nxb4  ,  exploiting the unprotected rook on a8.  25...Qxb4  26.Qxc6  Ra3=  . }
22... Rfd8
{ I defended the pawn without spending too much time, but it is rarely the best choice in our opening.   22...Ra2  23.Ra1   23.Qxd6  ,  I didn't play ...Ra2 because I made a mistake in calculating this variation.  23...Rd8  24.Qxc6  Qxc6  25.Rxd8+  Kh7  26.Nxb4  Qb6  27.Nxa2  and I stopped here, a rookie mistake. Obviously, Black can capture the rook and has a favorable game:  27...Qxd8⩱  .  23...Rfa8  24.Rxa2  Rxa2  25.Bh3!  As Black wants to trade dark-squared bishops, White's strategic dream is to exchange the light-squared ones.  25...Qc7=  . }
23. Ra1 Qb6 24. Rfd1
{ White leaves Black the decision on how to unbalance the position. This is a clever strategy against weaker players because making decisions is one of the hardest things, leaving more chances to go wrong.   24.Rxa8  Rxa8  25.Bh3  @@StartBracket@@  25.Qxd6??  Rd8  26.c5  Qb7-+  and the queen is lost.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r5k1/5pb1/1qnpb1p1/4p2p/1pP1P2P/1P1QN1PB/2N2P1K/5R2 b - - 1 25@@EndFEN@@  25...Qc5  26.Bxe6  fxe6=  ,  Black solves the problems with the light squares and has the a-file, but the structure is worse. }
24... Ra5 { Trying to double rooks on the open file. } 25. Bh3
{ White hopes for ...Bxh3, while Black ignores the bishop. } 25... Kh7
{ 25...Rxa1  26.Rxa1  Nb8!  As we learned in the strategical themes, Black improves the worst piece.  27.Ra4  Na6  ,  just in time to defend b4.  28.Qe2  Bh6=  . }
26. Kg2 Bf8
{ I was not precise in this phase of the game; as I mentioned before, I was low on time, and she was pressing.   26...Bh6!  Another typical maneuver to exchange minor pieces if needed.  27.Nd5  Bxd5  28.cxd5  Nd4  29.Rxa5  Qxa5  30.Nxd4  exd4  31.Qxd4  Bg7  32.Qc4  Ra8=∞  and at the end of the simplifications, the chances are equal. }
27. Rxa5
{ 27.Nd5!?  Bxd5  28.exd5  Nd4  29.Nxd4  Rxa1  30.Rxa1  Qxd4  31.Qxd4  exd4±  , when  the bishop would be more active on h6. }
27... Nxa5 28. Ra1 Nb7 { Different path, same plan. The knight belongs to c5. }
29. Nd5 Nc5 { A critical intermediate move. } 30. Qf3
{ I remember I was afraid of this line:  30.Nxb6!?  Nxd3  31.Bxe6  fxe6  32.Ra7+  Kh6  ,  but Black is doing fine. }
30... Bxd5 { My chance to get ahead. } 31. cxd5 Qb7
{ 31...Kg8⩱  was essential, to prevent the tactic with Nxb4. } 32. g4
{ 32.Nxb4!  Qxb4  33.Qxf7+  Bg7  ,  of course, I saw this idea, but I thought I had enough compensation thanks to the weaknesses on b3 and e4.  34.Ra7  Nd7  ,  the only way to avoid the checkmate.  35.Rxd7  Rxd7  36.Bxd7  Qxe4+  37.Kh2⩲  and White has a slight edge because of the passed pawn. }
32... hxg4 33. Bxg4 Bh6 { Being ready to capture if Ne3. } 34. h5
{ 34.Nxb4  Rf8  35.Nd3  Nxe4!  36.Qxe4  f5  is another demonstration that the Sveshnikov is full of tactical blows.  37.Qb4  Qxd5+  38.Bf3  e4  ,  I like this line because it is full of counterblows.  39.Ra7+  Rf7  40.Rxf7+  Qxf7  41.Qxd6  exf3+  42.Kxf3  Qxb3=  and Black equalizes. }
34... Kg7 { Putting the pieces on squares of the same color as our bishop. }
35. Rh1 Rh8
{ The fight for the file shifts the rook to the other side of the board. } 36.
hxg6 fxg6 37. Be6 Bf4
{ 37...Qe7!  Suddenly, Black has a considerable advantage.  38.Qg4  @@StartBracket@@  38.Rh3?  Rf8  39.Qe2  Qg5+  40.Rg3  Qd2  41.Qxd2  Bxd2-+  and Black wins because of the activity.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@7r/4q1k1/3pB1pb/2nPp3/1p2P1Q1/1P6/2N2PK1/7R b - - 3 38@@EndFEN@@  38...Nd3∓  . }
38. Rxh8 Kxh8 39. Bh3 { 39.Nd4!  Qh7  40.Nc6  Qh2+  41.Kf1  Kg7= } 39... Kg7
40. Kg1 Bd2 { Reaching the time control with a slight advantage. } 41. Ne3 Bxe3
42. Qxe3 Qf7
{ I planned to trade queens and win the minor pieces endgame thanks to the weakness on b3. }
43. Bg2 Qf4 44. Qe1
{ My opponent defended very well.  44.Qxf4??  exf4  45.Kf1  @@StartBracket@@  45.e5  dxe5  46.d6  Kf7  47.Bd5+  Ke8-+  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@8/6k1/3p2p1/2nP4/1p2Pp2/1P6/5PB1/5K2 b - - 1 45@@EndFEN@@  45...Nxb3  46.Ke1  Kf6  and Black wins. }
44... Nd3 45. Qe2 Qc1+ 46. Kh2 Qh6+ 47. Kg1 Qc1+ 48. Kh2 Ne1
{ I tried everything to reach victory. } 49. Qg4 Qf4+ 50. Qxf4 exf4
{ White to move: How to hold the endgame? } 51. e5
{ A splendid resource that I underestimated entirely. White frees the way for the bishop and arrives just in time to defend. }
51... dxe5 52. Be4
{ Black's knight seems to be in trouble now. Can you find the only move? }
52... f3 { Giving the knight the g2-square. } 53. Kg3 Kf6 54. Kg4 Ke7 55. Bxg6
Kd6 56. Be4 Ng2 57. Kxf3 Nf4 58. Ke3 Nxd5+ 59. Kd3 Nb6
{ In my opinion, this is a very complex and exciting game with many themes that we learned during the course: the typical knight maneuver, how to deal with the c4 structure, fighting for the a-file, playing with the opposite-colored bishops, the poisoned d6-pawn. We both had our chances to try to win, but more precision was required to get the entire point. }
