1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 Nxd5 8.
exd5 Nb8 9. c4
{ Even though it is the most played, the critical continuation is  9.a4  . }
9... Be7 10. Be2
{ With the c4-pawn defending d5, the white bishop is usually more active on d3.   10.Bd3  O-O  11.O-O  a6  12.Nc3  f5  is covered in the theoretical part. }
10... O-O 11. O-O
{ I did not remember the exact order, so I decided to wait for Be3 to push the pawn.  11...a6  is the most common. }
11... Nd7 12. Be3
{ When White has already castled, there are no more tactical ideas with ...Qa5+, which means the a7-pawn is hanging. }
12... a6 13. Nc3 f5
{ I played this game while working on the course, so my mind was full of different ideas. Sometimes, knowing too much can make us more confused. In my opponent's time, I was thinking about how to react against  14.f4  and if it was possible to win a pawn after  14...exf4  15.Bxf4  Qb6+  followed by ...Qxb2. }
14. f3
{ 14.f4  Bf6  ,  the best answer is to continue with development, not being too greedy.   14...exf4  is good too.  15.Bxf4   15.Rxf4?  Bg5  16.Qd4  ,  White is forced to sacrifice the exchange.   16.Rf3  Bxe3+  17.Rxe3  Qb6  ,  the pin is fatal.  18.Qd3  f4-+  16...Re8!  is more precise because it occupies the unique open file of the board and avoids any rook retreat by putting pressure on the bishop on e3.   16...Bxf4  17.Qxf4  Qe7∓  is the human way to take a modest advantage.  17.Bf2  Bxf4  18.Qxf4  Ne5-+  ,  the material imbalance makes a huge difference.  15...b6  ,  going for the same plan of the game.   15...Qb6+  16.Kh1  Qxb2  is the line I was calculating during the game. It looks like the Najdorf's poisoned pawn. It is possible, but it is preferable not to waste so many tempi to capture a pawn.  17.Na4  Qf6  18.c5!  A difficult move to find, White wants to sacrifice another pawn to open the lines for the pieces.  18...Rb8  ,  but Black doesn't accept it!   After  18...Nxc5?  19.Nxc5  dxc5  20.d6+-  ,  White is winning due to the vulnerable black king and the strong passed pawn on d6.  19.Rc1  b5  ,  in Benoni's style.  20.cxb6  Nxb6⩲  ,  with a slight edge for White. The activity compensates for the pawn.  15.Qd2  @@StartBracket@@  15.fxe5  Bxe5  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p1n2pp/p2p1b2/3Ppp2/2P2P2/2N1B3/PP1QB1PP/R4RK1 b - - 2 15@@EndFEN@@  15...b6  slowly improving the position until White captures on e5. }
14... Bg5
{ Every strong player says it is better to understand the key ideas of the middlegame when learning an opening because memory can fail but general comprehension usually doesn't. I was not sure ...Bg5 was the move, but I knew that Black should attack the kingside using the dark squares and bring the queen via f6 to h6. }
15. Qd2
{ Forcing Black to play ...Bxe3. As we repeated many times, trading the dark-squared bishops strategically favors Black, who has the pawns on the dark squares.   After  15.Bf2  Qf6  ,  Black has great attacking chances. }
15... Bxe3+ 16. Qxe3 a5 { Securing the c5-square for the knight. } 17. f4
{ White wants to force ...Nxe5 to remove the defender of the c5-square and achieve a pawn break.   After  17.b3  Nc5  18.Bd1  Bd7=  ,  Black has equality and leaves White without a clear plan. }
17... Re8
{ Since the e-file will be opened, I decided to fight for control of it. } 18.
fxe5
{ The first mistake.   18.Bd3  Nc5  19.Bc2  Bd7  20.Kh1  Qf6  21.fxe5  Rxe5  22.Qf2  Rae8  23.Rad1  g6  24.h3  Kg7  25.Qf4  g5  26.Qf2  f4  27.Bb1  a4  28.b4  axb3  29.axb3  Re3  30.b4  Qxc3  31.bxc5  Bxh3  32.cxd6  Bxg2+  33.Kxg2  Re2  34.d7  Rxf2+  35.Rxf2  Qg3+  36.Kf1  Qh3+  37.Rg2  Qf3+  0-1 Kasimdzhanov-Carlsen, Wch Blitz, Moscow 2007. }
18... Rxe5 19. Qf2 Nc5
{ The white knight must protect the e4-square. Otherwise, the black one on c5 would immediately jump to the center. }
20. Rfe1
{ I didn't expect this move, but it follows the logical purpose of fighting for the open file going away with the bishop on f1.   20.Bd1  ,  the most accurate plan is redirecting the bishop to c2 to control the weak squares d3 and e4.  20...Bd7  21.Bc2  Qf6⩱  and thanks to the domain of the dark squares, Black is slightly better.   20.Rae1  Bd7  ,  White cannot move the bishop due to ...Nd3. }
20... Bd7 { It is essential to avoid White's improvement with Nb5-d4. } 21. Bf1
Rxe1
{ It may seem weird to deliberately give up the e-file, but White has no entries. }
22. Rxe1 Qf6 { The white rook looks active, but it is not helpful. } 23. Kh1
{ After  23.Qd2  h6  24.Re2  g5∓  ,  Black is ready to expand on the kingside and has a favorable game. }
23... Rf8
{ I underestimated my position. I evaluated it as approximately equal; instead, Black is clearly better thanks to the activity on the kingside. }
24. Rd1
{ I thought my opponent wanted to prepare Qd4, but then I understood that the idea was to put the bishop on d3. }
24... Qh6
{ Not the most precise but logical; if White doesn't pay attention, the black knight can jump to e4, and the rook on f8 can put pressure on f1. }
25. Bd3 f4
{ Now that the white bishop no longer defends the king, it is time to start the attack. White must find an only move to stay in the game. }
26. Bc2
{ 26.Be4□  ,  White needs to stop the ...f3 push. Following  26...g5  27.Kg1  g4⩱  ,  Black's chances of victory are high because of the initiative against the opponent's king. }
26... f3 { The white king is very exposed, and Black is ready to assault it. }
27. Rf1
{ 27.gxf3?  Bg4-+  ,  White cannot defend from ...Bxf3.   27.g3  leaves significative weaknesses on the light squares.  27...Bf5   27...Bh3  is the move I would have played.  28.Ne4  Nd7  ,  if the black knight arrives at g4, the game ends.  29.Qd2  Qh5-+  ,  we don't want to exchange queens because we're the attacking side. Black has a big advantage.  28.Bxf5  Rxf5-+  and Black is winning. }
27... Bg4
{ I protected the f3-pawn and prepared a little trap against the predictable move Ne4. }
28. Ne4
{ 28.Kg1  ,  forcing Black to find the only correct plan to win.  28...Nd7!  The knight belongs to e5. The attack is crushing. }
28... fxg2+ 29. Qxg2 Rxf1+ 30. Qxf1 Qe3
{ A silent but lethal move: the threat is ...Bf3+ and White loses material. }
31. Qf2 { 31.Nf2  Bf3+  32.Kg1  Qg5+  33.Ng4  Qxg4+-+ } 31... Bf3+
{ My opponent resigned in view of: } 32. Kg1 Qc1+ 33. Qf1 Qxf1+ 34. Kxf1 Bxe4
{ The extra piece gives Black the entire point. I particularly liked this game because I won without doing anything special. It is an excellent example of how White players can quickly lose if they don't create counterplay on the queenside by pushing the majority.  My opponent didn't make many mistakes; he released the central tension too early with fxe5 and then found the correct plan of redirecting the bishop to the b1-h7 diagonal but did it at the wrong time. Defending the kingside is never easy for White in this structure. }
*

